{"title_page": "Yaakov Perlow", "text_new": "{{short description|American rabbi}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox Jewish leader \n| honorific-prefix = Grand Rabbi\n| name             = Rav Yaakov Perlow\n| honorific-suffix = \n| title            = [[Novominsk (Hasidic dynasty)|Novominsker]] [[Rebbe]]\n| image            = \n| caption          = \n| synagogue        = \n| synagogueposition = \n| yeshiva          = Yeshivas Novominsk Kol Yehuda\n| yeshivaposition  = [[Rosh yeshiva]]\n| organisation     = [[Agudath Israel of America]]\n| organisationposition = President\n| began            = December 1998\n| ended            = \n| predecessor      = Rabbi [[Moshe Sherer]]\n| successor        = \n| rabbi            = \n| rebbe            = \n| kohan            = \n| hazzan           = \n| rank             = \n| other_post       = Member of [[Moetzes Gedolei HaTorah]] (Council of Torah Sages)\n<!---------- Personal details ---------->\n| birth_date       = 1931\n| birth_place      = [[Brooklyn]], New York\n| death_date       = {{death date and age|2020|4|7|1931}}\n| death_place      = Brooklyn, New York\n| yahrtzeit        = \n| buried           = \n| nationality      = United States\n| denomination     = \n| residence        = \n| dynasty          = [[Novominsk (Hasidic dynasty)]]\n| parents          = \n| father           = Rabbi Nochum Mordechai Perlow\n| mother           = Beila Rochma Morgenstern\n| spouse           = \n| children         = \n| occupation       = \n| profession       = \n| alma_mater       = [[Yeshiva Rabbi Chaim Berlin]]<br>[[Beth Medrash Govoha]]\n| semicha          = \n}}\n'''Yaakov Perlow''' (1931 \u2013 April 7, 2020) was an American [[Hasidic Judaism|Hasidic]] rabbi and [[rosh yeshiva]], and [[Rebbe]] of the [[Novominsk (Hasidic dynasty)|Novominsker]] [[List of Hasidic dynasties|Hasidic dynasty]]. From 1998 until his death, he was president of [[Agudath Israel of America]], a [[Haredi Judaism|Haredi]] advocacy organization. He was also a member of the [[Moetzes Gedolei HaTorah]] (Council of Torah Sages) of Agudath Israel of America. He was one of the most respected leaders of the American Orthodox community, known for his scholarly and oratorical skills.<ref name=bhol/>\n\n==Early life and education==\nYaakov Perlow was born in [[Brooklyn]], New York, to Rabbi Nochum Mordechai Perlow (1887\u20131976), the Novominsker Rebbe, and his wife, Beila Rochma Morgenstern.<ref name=\"matzav\">{{cite web|url=http://matzav.com/todays-yahrtzeits-and-history-9-elul-2/|title=Today's Yahrtzeits and History \u2013 9 Elul|date=August 24, 2015|publisher=matzav.com|accessdate=August 25, 2016}}</ref> He was named after his paternal grandfather, the founder of the Novominsk Hasidic dynasty.<ref name=bhol>{{cite web |url=https://www.bhol.co.il/news/1092156|title=\u05d0\u05d1\u05dc \u05d1\u05d9\u05d4\u05d3\u05d5\u05ea \u05d4\u05d7\u05e8\u05d3\u05d9\u05ea: \u05d4\u05e8\u05d1\u05d9 \u05de\u05e0\u05d5\u05d1\u05d5\u05de\u05d9\u05e0\u05e1\u05e7 \u05d6\u05e6\"\u05dc \u05e8\u05d0\u05e9 \u05d0\u05d2\u05d5\"\u05d9 \u05d1\u05d0\u05de\u05e8\u05d9\u05e7\u05d4 |language=Hebrew|trans-title=Mourning in Haredi Judaism: The Novominsker Rebbe, zt'l, Head of Agudath Israel in America|first=Moshe|last=Weisberg|date=7 April 2020|accessdate=7 April 2020|work=Behadrei Chareidim}}</ref> His maternal grandfather was Rabbi [[Yitzchak Zelig Morgenstern]], the Sokolover Rebbe, a direct descendant of Rabbi [[Menachem Mendel of Kotzk]].<ref name=bhol/><ref name=\"pol\">{{cite web|url=http://poznan.jewish.org.pl/index.php/portrety/Zapomniany-rabin.html|title=Zapomniany rabin|last=Markusz|first=Katarzyna|publisher=poznan.jewish.org.pl|language=Polish|trans-title=Forgotten Rabbi|accessdate=August 25, 2016}}</ref> Morgernstern was one of the main founders of [[World Agudath Israel|Agudath Israel]] in Poland.<ref name=\"matzav\" /><ref name=\"new\" />\n\nPerlow began his Torah education at Yeshiva Toras Chaim in [[East New York]], and continued on to the [[Lithuanian Jews|Lithuanian]]-type yeshivas of Yeshiva Rabbi Chaim Berlin in Brooklyn and [[Beth Medrash Govoha]] in [[Lakewood Township, New Jersey|Lakewood]], New Jersey.<ref name=steve>{{cite web|url=https://web.stevens.edu/golem/llevine/ry_interviews/Interviews%20with%20RYs.pdf|title=Interviews conducted by Professor William Helmreich with various Roshei Yeshiva Helmreich with various Roshei Yeshiva |publisher=Stevens Institute of Technology|date=December 28, 1977|accessdate=August 25, 2016|pages=10\u201320}}</ref>{{sfn|Helmreich|2000|p=369}} He also graduated with honors from [[Brooklyn College]].{{sfn|Helmreich|2000|p=369}}{{sfn|Heilman|1995|p=326}}\n\n== Career ==\nPerlow subsequently taught at [[Hebrew Theological College]] in [[Skokie, Illinois]].<ref name=\"steve\" /> From there, he was appointed [[rosh yeshiva]] at the Breuer's yeshiva, Yeshiva Rabbi Samson Refael Hirsch, in [[Washington Heights, Manhattan|Washington Heights]], New York,<ref name=\"kaj\">{{cite web |url= http://www.kajinc.org/about/history|title= The Kehilla \u2013 A Brief Historical Overview|publisher=[[K'hal Adath Jeshurun]]|year=2016|accessdate=August 25, 2016}}</ref> and established a synagogue continuing the Novominsker Hasidic movement. After the death of his father, he began serving as Novominsker Rebbe. He established the Novominsk Hasidic Center and founded his own yeshiva, Yeshivas Novominsk Kol Yehuda, in [[Borough Park, Brooklyn]].<ref name=bhol/>\n\n===Agudath Israel of America===\nIn December 1998, Perlow was named president of the [[Agudath Israel of America]] organization, succeeding Rabbi [[Moshe Sherer]], who had died seven months earlier.<ref name=\"new\">{{cite web |url= https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-22213037.html|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20161008195646/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-22213037.html|url-status= dead|archive-date= October 8, 2016|title= Novominsker Rebbe Emerges as New Sage of Aguda: Perlow Assumes Mantle|work=The Forward|date=December 4, 1998|accessdate=August 25, 2016|url-access=subscription |via=[[HighBeam Research|HighBeam]]}}</ref> With his appointment, the presidential and leadership duties held by Sherer were divided between Perlow, the new president, and a three-man executive.<ref name=\"new\" /> Perlow was also a member of the organization's [[Moetzes Gedolei HaTorah]] (Council of Torah Sages).{{Cn|date=April 2020}}\n\nPerlow frequently spoke out on issues affecting the American Orthodox Jewish world, including Internet usage,<ref name=\"oren\">{{cite web |url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-89108880.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161008195841/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-89108880.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=October 8, 2016|title=In Other Words|work=[[The Forward]]|first=Oren|last=Rawls|date=December 5, 2003|accessdate=August 25, 2016|quote='The Internet, with the flick of a button, invades a Jewish home, a Jewish soul, and makes moral disaster. And it is happening all the time', warns the highly-respected Rabbi Yaakov Perlow in The Jewish Observer, the house organ of the organization he heads, Agudath Israel of America.}}</ref> child abuse,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://yated.com/call-to-action/ |title=Call to Action|work=[[Yated Ne'eman (United States)|Yated Ne'eman]]|date=June 22, 2016|accessdate=August 26, 2016|quote=The Novominsker Rebbe, Rav Yaakov Perlow, issued a call for action in response to the festering scourge of child abuse and molestation.}}</ref> [[Holocaust denial]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://matzav.com/novominsker-rebbe-condemns-holocaust-comments-of-rabbi-on-video-publicized-by-matzav-com/|title=Novominsker Rebbe Condemns Holocaust Comments of Rabbi on Video Publicized by Matzav.com|date=January 6, 2016|accessdate=August 26, 2016|publisher=matzav.com|first=Gavriel |last=Sitrit|quote=I condemn in the strongest terms possible the outrageous claim that fewer than a million halachic Jews were killed in the Holocaust.}}</ref> overpriced Jewish weddings,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-79394097.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161008195810/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-79394097.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=October 8, 2016|title= Waiter, Hold The Knishes: Agudah urges cutting back on pricey weddings|first=Debra Nussbaum|last=Cohen|date=December 7, 2001|accessdate=August 26, 2016|work=[[The Jewish Week]]|url-access=subscription |via=HighBeam|quote=These rabbis, led by Yaakov Perlow, the chief religious authority of the fervently Orthodox organization Agudath Israel of America, are leading a charge to change the communal culture around frum weddings, where even families of moderate means feel social pressure to invite upward of 1,000 people and serve them food from lavish smorgasbords set with everything from intricate ice sculptures to glatt kosher prime rib carving stations.}}</ref> and U.S. politics.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-102216388.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161008195626/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-102216388.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=October 8, 2016 |title=Senator Presses for 2004, Before Focusing on Own Ambition|first=Joshua|last=Runyan|date=September 9, 2004|accessdate=August 26, 2016|work=The Jewish Exponent|url-access=subscription |via=HighBeam|quote=[Rick] Santorum and first-term Sen. Norm Coleman (R-Minn.) sat with Orthodox leaders during a closed-door meeting at Yeshivas Novominsk Kol Yehuda. After the meeting, Santorum said that he took to heart a message delivered to him by the Novominsker Rebbe, Rabbi Yaakov Perlow, and that he would try to incorporate that message into his convention address. \"I won't have time to mention my visit, but I will have the time to transmit the words of the rebbe upstairs, the importance of faith communities and making sure those communities can transmit their faith,\" he said.}}</ref> In 2015, Perlow shocked attendees at the 93rd annual Agudath Israel of America dinner by directly appealing to [[Barack Obama|President Obama]] to reconsider the [[Joint Comprehensive Plan of Action|Iran deal]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.theyeshivaworld.com/news/headlines-breaking-stories/309218/photos-novominsker-rebbe-issues-direct-plea-to-president-obama-at-agudath-israel-dinner.html|title= Novominsker Rebbe Issues Direct Plea to President Obama at Agudath Israel Dinner |date=May 12, 2015|accessdate=August 26, 2016|work=[[Yeshiva World News]]}}</ref>\n\nPerlow is seen as a controversial figure by some non-Orthodox Jewish groups in light of his comments about [[heterodoxy|heterodox]] Jewish movements. While he consistently calls for increased dialogue and rapprochement with non-Orthodox Jews, he couples that with condemnation of the non-Orthodox movements themselves. At the 73rd annual Agudah convention in 1995, he urged dialogue with non-Orthodox Jews while at the same time \"lashing out at what he described as the 'false ideology' of non-Orthodox Judaism.\"<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.jta.org/1995/11/28/archive/agudath-israel-leader-calls-for-dialogue-as-he-lashes-out |title= Agudath Israel Leader Calls for Dialogue As He Lashes Out|date=November 28, 1995|accessdate=August 26, 2016|publisher=[[Jewish Telegraphic Agency|JTA]]}}</ref> In June 1999, he wrote in ''[[The Jewish Observer]]'' in support of a rapprochement in the long-standing feud between the Haredi and Reform movements.{{sfn|Ferziger|2015|pp=136\u2013139}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-22426699.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161008195701/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-22426699.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=October 8, 2016|title=Perlow's Progress|work=The Forward|date=January 8, 1999|accessdate=August 26, 2016|url-access=subscription |via=HighBeam}}</ref> At the May 2014 Agudath dinner, he stated that the Reform and Conservative movements \"have disintegrated themselves, become oblivious, fallen into an abyss of intermarriage and assimilation,\"<ref name=\"nyt\" /><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.haaretz.com/jewish/rabbis-round-table/.premium-1.597797|title= Fair Criticism, Flawed Justification: Where Rabbi Perlow Went Wrong|first=Dr. Samuel|last=Lebens|date=June 9, 2014|accessdate=August 26, 2016|work=[[Haaretz]]}}</ref> and branded another movement, [[Open Orthodoxy]], as being \"steeped in apikorsos\" (heresy).<ref name=\"ny\">{{cite web |url= http://forward.com/news/199010/orthodox-rabbi-stuns-agudath-gala-with-heresy-atta/|title= Orthodox Rabbi Stuns Agudath Gala With 'Heresy' Attack on Open Orthodoxy|first=Josh|last=Nathan-Kazis|date=May 28, 2014|accessdate=August 25, 2016|work=The Forward}}</ref> While New York City Mayor [[Bill de Blasio]] was the next speaker at the dinner, he did not challenge Perlow's remarks, which cast aspersions on the affiliations of the non-Orthodox Jewish population of New York City.<ref name=\"nyt\">{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/05/29/nyregion/at-a-jewish-gala-de-blasio-skips-his-cue-to-speak-out.html?_r=0|title=At a Jewish Gala, de Blasio Skips His Cue to Speak Out|first=Michael|last=Powell|date=May 28, 2014|accessdate=August 26, 2016|work=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://observer.com/2014/05/bill-de-blasio-furiously-refuses-to-denounce-rabbi-tirade/|title= Bill de Blasio Furiously Refuses to Denounce Rabbi Tirade|first=Ross|last=Barkan|date=May 30, 2014|accessdate=August 26, 2016|work=[[New York Observer]]}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nPerlow's wife Yehudit is the daughter of Grand Rabbi Avrohom Eichenstein of [[Zidichov (Hasidic dynasty)|Zidichov]]-Chicago.<ref name=bhol/>\n\nOn April 7, 2020, Perlow died due to complications from [[COVID-19]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Agudath Israel leader succumbs to coronavirus |url=https://jewishinsider.com/2020/04/agudath-israel-leader-succumbs-to-coronavirus/ |accessdate=April 7, 2020 |agency=jewishinsider.com}}</ref> His funeral was held in a private ceremony, with eulogies and the saying of [[Psalm]]s broadcast live via telephone, in keeping with health regulations curtailing the spread of the coronavirus.<ref name=bhol/>\n\n==Bibliography==\n*''Eidat Yaakov'' on Shas ([[Talmud]])\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n*{{cite book|ref=harv|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Y1RQCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA136 |title=Beyond Sectarianism: The Realignment of American Orthodox Judaism|first=Adam S.|last=Ferziger|year=2015|publisher=Wayne State University Press|isbn=0814339549}}\n*{{cite book|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GxwUCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA326|title=The Americanization of the Jews|chapter=The Ninth Siyum HaShas: A Case Study in Orthodox Contra-Acculturation|first=Samuel C.|authorlink=Samuel Heilman|last=Heilman|editor-first=Robert|editor-last=Seltzer|year=1995|publisher=NYU Press|isbn=0814780008|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/americanizationo0000unse_f9c0}}\n*{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lFvQ79N9vIAC&pg=PA369 |title=The World of the Yeshiva: An Intimate Portrait of Orthodox Jewry|first=William B.|last=Helmreich|year=2000|publisher=KTAV Publishing House, Inc.|isbn=0881256420}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20161008194128/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1A2-8005ae5ca5e54a37a22fd6bab64c8943.html Photo of Rabbi Yaakov Perlow] at the [[Siyum HaShas#12th Siyum HaShas|12th Siyum HaShas]], August 2, 2012\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tM0GUFylNKs \u201cCity Council candidate John Heyer meets with Rabbi Yaakov Perlow and Rabbi Shmuel Lefkowitz\u201d (video)] September 4, 2009\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Perlow, Yaakov}}\n[[Category:1931 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:Hasidic rebbes]]\n[[Category:Hasidic rosh yeshivas]]\n[[Category:American Hasidic rabbis]]\n[[Category:American people of Polish-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:Moetzes Gedolei HaTorah]]\n[[Category:People from Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:20th-century rabbis]]\n[[Category:21st-century rabbis]]\n[[Category:Deaths from the 2020 coronavirus pandemic in New York (state)]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American rabbi}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox Jewish leader \n| honorific-prefix = Grand Rabbi\n| name             = Rav Yaakov Perlow\n| honorific-suffix = \n| title            = [[Novominsk (Hasidic dynasty)|Novominsker]] [[Rebbe]]\n| image            = \n| caption          = \n| synagogue        = \n| synagogueposition = \n| yeshiva          = Yeshivas Novominsk Kol Yehuda\n| yeshivaposition  = [[Rosh yeshiva]]\n| organisation     = [[Agudath Israel of America]]\n| organisationposition = President\n| began            = December 1998\n| ended            = \n| predecessor      = Rabbi [[Moshe Sherer]]\n| successor        = \n| rabbi            = \n| rebbe            = \n| kohan            = \n| hazzan           = \n| rank             = \n| other_post       = Member of [[Moetzes Gedolei HaTorah]] (Council of Torah Sages)\n<!---------- Personal details ---------->\n| birth_date       = 1931\n| birth_place      = [[Brooklyn]], New York\n| death_date       = {{death date and age|2020|4|7|1931}}\n| death_place      = Brooklyn, New York\n| yahrtzeit        = \n| buried           = \n| nationality      = United States\n| denomination     = \n| residence        = \n| dynasty          = [[Novominsk (Hasidic dynasty)]]\n| parents          = \n| father           = Rabbi Nochum Mordechai Perlow\n| mother           = Beila Rochma Morgenstern\n| spouse           = \n| children         = \n| occupation       = \n| profession       = \n| alma_mater       = [[Yeshiva Rabbi Chaim Berlin]]<br>[[Beth Medrash Govoha]]\n| semicha          = \n}}\n'''Yaakov Perlow''' (1931 \u2013 April 7, 2020) was an American [[Hasidic Judaism|Hasidic]] rabbi and [[rosh yeshiva]], and [[Rebbe]] of the [[Novominsk (Hasidic dynasty)|Novominsker]] [[List of Hasidic dynasties|Hasidic dynasty]]. From 1998 until his death, he was president of [[Agudath Israel of America]], a [[Haredi Judaism|Haredi]] advocacy organization. He was also a member of the [[Moetzes Gedolei HaTorah]] (Council of Torah Sages) of Agudath Israel of America. He was one of the most respected leaders of the American Orthodox community, known for his scholarly and oratorical skills.<ref name=bhol/>\n\n==Early life and education==\nYaakov Perlow was born in [[Brooklyn]], New York, to Rabbi Nochum Mordechai Perlow (1887\u20131976), the Novominsker Rebbe, and his wife, Beila Rochma Morgenstern.<ref name=\"matzav\">{{cite web|url=http://matzav.com/todays-yahrtzeits-and-history-9-elul-2/|title=Today's Yahrtzeits and History \u2013 9 Elul|date=August 24, 2015|publisher=matzav.com|accessdate=August 25, 2016}}</ref> He was named after his paternal grandfather, the founder of the Novominsk Hasidic dynasty.<ref name=bhol>{{cite web |url=https://www.bhol.co.il/news/1092156|title=\u05d0\u05d1\u05dc \u05d1\u05d9\u05d4\u05d3\u05d5\u05ea \u05d4\u05d7\u05e8\u05d3\u05d9\u05ea: \u05d4\u05e8\u05d1\u05d9 \u05de\u05e0\u05d5\u05d1\u05d5\u05de\u05d9\u05e0\u05e1\u05e7 \u05d6\u05e6\"\u05dc \u05e8\u05d0\u05e9 \u05d0\u05d2\u05d5\"\u05d9 \u05d1\u05d0\u05de\u05e8\u05d9\u05e7\u05d4 |language=Hebrew|trans-title=Mourning in Haredi Judaism: The Novominsker Rebbe, zt'l, Head of Agudath Israel in America|first=Moshe|last=Weisberg|date=7 April 2020|accessdate=7 April 2020|work=Behadrei Chareidim}}</ref> His maternal grandfather was Rabbi [[Yitzchak Zelig Morgenstern]], the Sokolover Rebbe, a direct descendant of Rabbi [[Menachem Mendel of Kotzk]].<ref name=bhol/> <ref name=\"pol\">{{cite web|url=http://poznan.jewish.org.pl/index.php/portrety/Zapomniany-rabin.html|title=Zapomniany rabin|last=Markusz|first=Katarzyna|publisher=poznan.jewish.org.pl|language=Polish|trans-title=Forgotten Rabbi|accessdate=August 25, 2016}}</ref> Morgernstern was one of the main founders of [[World Agudath Israel|Agudath Israel]] in Poland.<ref name=\"matzav\" /><ref name=\"new\" />\n\nPerlow began his Torah education at Yeshiva Toras Chaim in [[East New York]], and continued on to the [[Lithuanian Jews|Lithuanian]]-type yeshivas of Yeshiva Rabbi Chaim Berlin in Brooklyn and [[Beth Medrash Govoha]] in [[Lakewood Township, New Jersey|Lakewood]], New Jersey.<ref name=steve>{{cite web|url=https://web.stevens.edu/golem/llevine/ry_interviews/Interviews%20with%20RYs.pdf|title=Interviews conducted by Professor William Helmreich with various Roshei Yeshiva Helmreich with various Roshei Yeshiva |publisher=Stevens Institute of Technology|date=December 28, 1977|accessdate=August 25, 2016|pages=10\u201320}}</ref>{{sfn|Helmreich|2000|p=369}} He also graduated with honors from [[Brooklyn College]].{{sfn|Helmreich|2000|p=369}}{{sfn|Heilman|1995|p=326}}\n\n== Career ==\nPerlow subsequently taught at [[Hebrew Theological College]] in [[Skokie, Illinois]].<ref name=\"steve\" /> From there, he was appointed [[rosh yeshiva]] at the Breuer's yeshiva, Yeshiva Rabbi Samson Refael Hirsch, in [[Washington Heights, Manhattan|Washington Heights]], New York,<ref name=\"kaj\">{{cite web |url= http://www.kajinc.org/about/history|title= The Kehilla \u2013 A Brief Historical Overview|publisher=[[K'hal Adath Jeshurun]]|year=2016|accessdate=August 25, 2016}}</ref> and established a synagogue continuing the Novominsker Hasidic movement. After the death of his father, he began serving as Novominsker Rebbe. He established the Novominsk Hasidic Center and founded his own yeshiva, Yeshivas Novominsk Kol Yehuda, in [[Borough Park, Brooklyn]].<ref name=bhol/>\n\n===Agudath Israel of America===\nIn December 1998, Perlow was named president of the [[Agudath Israel of America]] organization, succeeding Rabbi [[Moshe Sherer]], who had died seven months earlier.<ref name=\"new\">{{cite web |url= https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-22213037.html|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20161008195646/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-22213037.html|url-status= dead|archive-date= October 8, 2016|title= Novominsker Rebbe Emerges as New Sage of Aguda: Perlow Assumes Mantle|work=The Forward|date=December 4, 1998|accessdate=August 25, 2016|url-access=subscription |via=[[HighBeam Research|HighBeam]]}}</ref> With his appointment, the presidential and leadership duties held by Sherer were divided between Perlow, the new president, and a three-man executive.<ref name=\"new\" /> Perlow was also a member of the organization's [[Moetzes Gedolei HaTorah]] (Council of Torah Sages).{{Cn|date=April 2020}}\n\nPerlow frequently spoke out on issues affecting the American Orthodox Jewish world, including Internet usage,<ref name=\"oren\">{{cite web |url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-89108880.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161008195841/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-89108880.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=October 8, 2016|title=In Other Words|work=[[The Forward]]|first=Oren|last=Rawls|date=December 5, 2003|accessdate=August 25, 2016|quote='The Internet, with the flick of a button, invades a Jewish home, a Jewish soul, and makes moral disaster. And it is happening all the time', warns the highly-respected Rabbi Yaakov Perlow in The Jewish Observer, the house organ of the organization he heads, Agudath Israel of America.}}</ref> child abuse,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://yated.com/call-to-action/ |title=Call to Action|work=[[Yated Ne'eman (United States)|Yated Ne'eman]]|date=June 22, 2016|accessdate=August 26, 2016|quote=The Novominsker Rebbe, Rav Yaakov Perlow, issued a call for action in response to the festering scourge of child abuse and molestation.}}</ref> [[Holocaust denial]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://matzav.com/novominsker-rebbe-condemns-holocaust-comments-of-rabbi-on-video-publicized-by-matzav-com/|title=Novominsker Rebbe Condemns Holocaust Comments of Rabbi on Video Publicized by Matzav.com|date=January 6, 2016|accessdate=August 26, 2016|publisher=matzav.com|first=Gavriel |last=Sitrit|quote=I condemn in the strongest terms possible the outrageous claim that fewer than a million halachic Jews were killed in the Holocaust.}}</ref> overpriced Jewish weddings,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-79394097.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161008195810/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-79394097.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=October 8, 2016|title= Waiter, Hold The Knishes: Agudah urges cutting back on pricey weddings|first=Debra Nussbaum|last=Cohen|date=December 7, 2001|accessdate=August 26, 2016|work=[[The Jewish Week]]|url-access=subscription |via=HighBeam|quote=These rabbis, led by Yaakov Perlow, the chief religious authority of the fervently Orthodox organization Agudath Israel of America, are leading a charge to change the communal culture around frum weddings, where even families of moderate means feel social pressure to invite upward of 1,000 people and serve them food from lavish smorgasbords set with everything from intricate ice sculptures to glatt kosher prime rib carving stations.}}</ref> and U.S. politics.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-102216388.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161008195626/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-102216388.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=October 8, 2016 |title=Senator Presses for 2004, Before Focusing on Own Ambition|first=Joshua|last=Runyan|date=September 9, 2004|accessdate=August 26, 2016|work=The Jewish Exponent|url-access=subscription |via=HighBeam|quote=[Rick] Santorum and first-term Sen. Norm Coleman (R-Minn.) sat with Orthodox leaders during a closed-door meeting at Yeshivas Novominsk Kol Yehuda. After the meeting, Santorum said that he took to heart a message delivered to him by the Novominsker Rebbe, Rabbi Yaakov Perlow, and that he would try to incorporate that message into his convention address. \"I won't have time to mention my visit, but I will have the time to transmit the words of the rebbe upstairs, the importance of faith communities and making sure those communities can transmit their faith,\" he said.}}</ref> In 2015, Perlow shocked attendees at the 93rd annual Agudath Israel of America dinner by directly appealing to [[Barack Obama|President Obama]] to reconsider the [[Joint Comprehensive Plan of Action|Iran deal]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.theyeshivaworld.com/news/headlines-breaking-stories/309218/photos-novominsker-rebbe-issues-direct-plea-to-president-obama-at-agudath-israel-dinner.html|title= Novominsker Rebbe Issues Direct Plea to President Obama at Agudath Israel Dinner |date=May 12, 2015|accessdate=August 26, 2016|work=[[Yeshiva World News]]}}</ref>\n\nPerlow is seen as a controversial figure by some non-Orthodox Jewish groups in light of his comments about [[heterodoxy|heterodox]] Jewish movements. While he consistently calls for increased dialogue and rapprochement with non-Orthodox Jews, he couples that with condemnation of the non-Orthodox movements themselves. At the 73rd annual Agudah convention in 1995, he urged dialogue with non-Orthodox Jews while at the same time \"lashing out at what he described as the 'false ideology' of non-Orthodox Judaism.\"<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.jta.org/1995/11/28/archive/agudath-israel-leader-calls-for-dialogue-as-he-lashes-out |title= Agudath Israel Leader Calls for Dialogue As He Lashes Out|date=November 28, 1995|accessdate=August 26, 2016|publisher=[[Jewish Telegraphic Agency|JTA]]}}</ref> In June 1999, he wrote in ''[[The Jewish Observer]]'' in support of a rapprochement in the long-standing feud between the Haredi and Reform movements.{{sfn|Ferziger|2015|pp=136\u2013139}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-22426699.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161008195701/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-22426699.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=October 8, 2016|title=Perlow's Progress|work=The Forward|date=January 8, 1999|accessdate=August 26, 2016|url-access=subscription |via=HighBeam}}</ref> At the May 2014 Agudath dinner, he stated that the Reform and Conservative movements \"have disintegrated themselves, become oblivious, fallen into an abyss of intermarriage and assimilation,\"<ref name=\"nyt\" /><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.haaretz.com/jewish/rabbis-round-table/.premium-1.597797|title= Fair Criticism, Flawed Justification: Where Rabbi Perlow Went Wrong|first=Dr. Samuel|last=Lebens|date=June 9, 2014|accessdate=August 26, 2016|work=[[Haaretz]]}}</ref> and branded another movement, [[Open Orthodoxy]], as being \"steeped in apikorsos\" (heresy).<ref name=\"ny\">{{cite web |url= http://forward.com/news/199010/orthodox-rabbi-stuns-agudath-gala-with-heresy-atta/|title= Orthodox Rabbi Stuns Agudath Gala With 'Heresy' Attack on Open Orthodoxy|first=Josh|last=Nathan-Kazis|date=May 28, 2014|accessdate=August 25, 2016|work=The Forward}}</ref> While New York City Mayor [[Bill de Blasio]] was the next speaker at the dinner, he did not challenge Perlow's remarks, which cast aspersions on the affiliations of the non-Orthodox Jewish population of New York City.<ref name=\"nyt\">{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/05/29/nyregion/at-a-jewish-gala-de-blasio-skips-his-cue-to-speak-out.html?_r=0|title=At a Jewish Gala, de Blasio Skips His Cue to Speak Out|first=Michael|last=Powell|date=May 28, 2014|accessdate=August 26, 2016|work=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://observer.com/2014/05/bill-de-blasio-furiously-refuses-to-denounce-rabbi-tirade/|title= Bill de Blasio Furiously Refuses to Denounce Rabbi Tirade|first=Ross|last=Barkan|date=May 30, 2014|accessdate=August 26, 2016|work=[[New York Observer]]}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nPerlow's wife Yehudit is the daughter of Grand Rabbi Avrohom Eichenstein of [[Zidichov (Hasidic dynasty)|Zidichov]]-Chicago.<ref name=bhol/>\n\nOn April 7, 2020, Perlow died due to complications from [[COVID-19]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Agudath Israel leader succumbs to coronavirus |url=https://jewishinsider.com/2020/04/agudath-israel-leader-succumbs-to-coronavirus/ |accessdate=April 7, 2020 |agency=jewishinsider.com}}</ref> His funeral was held in a private ceremony, with eulogies and the saying of [[Psalm]]s broadcast live via telephone, in keeping with health regulations curtailing the spread of the coronavirus.<ref name=bhol/>\n\n==Bibliography==\n*''Eidat Yaakov'' on Shas ([[Talmud]])\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n*{{cite book|ref=harv|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Y1RQCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA136 |title=Beyond Sectarianism: The Realignment of American Orthodox Judaism|first=Adam S.|last=Ferziger|year=2015|publisher=Wayne State University Press|isbn=0814339549}}\n*{{cite book|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GxwUCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA326|title=The Americanization of the Jews|chapter=The Ninth Siyum HaShas: A Case Study in Orthodox Contra-Acculturation|first=Samuel C.|authorlink=Samuel Heilman|last=Heilman|editor-first=Robert|editor-last=Seltzer|year=1995|publisher=NYU Press|isbn=0814780008|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/americanizationo0000unse_f9c0}}\n*{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lFvQ79N9vIAC&pg=PA369 |title=The World of the Yeshiva: An Intimate Portrait of Orthodox Jewry|first=William B.|last=Helmreich|year=2000|publisher=KTAV Publishing House, Inc.|isbn=0881256420}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20161008194128/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1A2-8005ae5ca5e54a37a22fd6bab64c8943.html Photo of Rabbi Yaakov Perlow] at the [[Siyum HaShas#12th Siyum HaShas|12th Siyum HaShas]], August 2, 2012\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tM0GUFylNKs \u201cCity Council candidate John Heyer meets with Rabbi Yaakov Perlow and Rabbi Shmuel Lefkowitz\u201d (video)] September 4, 2009\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Perlow, Yaakov}}\n[[Category:1931 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:Hasidic rebbes]]\n[[Category:Hasidic rosh yeshivas]]\n[[Category:American Hasidic rabbis]]\n[[Category:American people of Polish-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:Moetzes Gedolei HaTorah]]\n[