{"title_page": "BMW 7 Series (E38)", "text_new": "{{Infobox automobile\n| image = BMW 750i E38 (7719664024).jpg\n| name = BMW 7 Series (E38)\n| assembly = Germany: [[Dingolfing]] ([[BMW Group Plant Dingolfing|BMW Plant Dingolfing]])\n| caption = 2001 BMW 750i \n| manufacturer = [[BMW]]\n| production = April 1994\u2013July 27, 2001<br>340,242 units produced<ref name=\"bmw-grouparchiv.de\">https://bmw-grouparchiv.de/research/detail/index.xhtml?id=3843495</ref><ref name=DeAutosab90Kittler>{{cite book |last=Kittler |first=Eberhard |authorlink= |title= Deutsche Autos seit 1990, Band 5|edition=1.|year=2001 |publisher=Motorbuch Verlag |location=Stuttgart |isbn=3-613-02128-5}}</ref><ref>''Auto Katalog'', 2003 edition, p. 312. Note: Figures include early E65 production.</ref>\n| predecessor = [[BMW 7 Series (E32)]]\n| successor = [[BMW 7 Series (E65)]]\n| body_style = 4-door [[sedan (car)|sedan/saloon]]\n| class = [[Full-size]] [[luxury car]] ([[F-segment|F]])\n| related = [[Alpina B12]]\n| engine = {{unbulleted list | '''Petrol:''' | 2.8&nbsp;L [[BMW M52|''M52'']] I6 | 3.0&ndash;4.0&nbsp;L [[BMW M60|''M60'']] V8 | 3.5&ndash;4.4&nbsp;L [[BMW M62|''M62'']] V8 | 5.4&nbsp;L [[BMW M73|''M73'']] V12 | '''Diesel:''' | 2.5&nbsp;L [[BMW M51|''M51'']] [[turbocharged]] I6 | 2.9&nbsp;L [[BMW M57|''M57'']] turbocharged I6| 3.9&nbsp;L [[BMW M67|''M67'']] turbocharged V8 }}\n| layout = [[Front-engine, rear-wheel-drive layout|Front-engine, rear-wheel-drive]]\n| transmission = {{Unbulleted list\n  |5-speed [[manual transmission|manual]]\n  |6-speed manual\n  |5-speed [[automatic transmission|automatic]]\n  }}\n| length = '''SWB:''' {{convert|4984|mm|in|1|abbr=on}} <br>'''LWB:''' {{convert|5124|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}\n| width = {{convert|1862|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}\n| height = '''SWB:''' {{convert|1425|mm|in|1|abbr=on}} <br>'''LWB:''' {{convert|1435|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}\n| weight = {{convert|1710|-|2085|kg|lb||abbr=on}}\n| wheelbase = '''SWB:''' {{convert|2930|mm|in|1|abbr=on}} <br>'''LWB:''' {{convert|3070|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}\n| designer = Boyke Boyer (exterior: 1990&ndash;1991)\n}}\n\nProduced from April 1994 to 2001, the '''BMW E38''' was the third generation of the [[BMW 7 Series]]. The flagship represented an attractive evolution in design language of the prior [[BMW E32|E32]] generation. The new 7 was available with [[straight-six]], [[V8 engine|V8]] and [[V12 engine|V12]] petrol and straight-six and V8 diesel engines. In 2001, the E38 was replaced by the [[BMW E65|E65 7 Series]].\n\nThe E38 was the first car available with [[Airbag#Side tubular or curtain airbag|curtain airbags]]. It was also the first European car to offer [[automotive navigation system|satellite navigation]]<ref>{{cite web|title=20 JAHRE NAVIGATION Was ist aus ihnen geworden?|url=http://www.auto-motor-und-sport.de/testbericht/20-jahre-navigation-was-ist-aus-ihnen-geworden-8398683.html|website=auto-motor-und-sport.de/|accessdate=4 May 2017}}</ref> and the first BMW to offer an in-built television. The E38 was the first 7 Series to be available with a [[diesel engine]].\n\n== Development ==\nIn early 1988, development began on the third generation of the 7 Series.<ref name=\"topspeed\">{{cite web|title=BMW 7 Series - A Look Back|url=http://www.topspeed.com/cars/car-news/bmw-7-seriesa-look-back-ar168860.html|website=www.topspeed.com|accessdate=7 April 2017}}</ref> From 1988 to 1990 styling work was done initially under design director [[Claus Luthe]]<ref>{{cite web|title=BMW car designers|url=http://www.bmwism.com/bmws_designers.htm|website=www.bmwism.com|accessdate=7 April 2017|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6CN8mVEjO?url=http://www.bmwism.com/bmws_designers.htm|archive-date=2012-11-22|url-status = dead}}</ref> (through April 1990, taken over by Dr. [[Wolfgang Reitzle]]), when Boyke Boyer's concept design was chosen and further refined into production form.<ref>{{cite web|title=BMW-Flaggschiff mit V8 f\u00fcr kleines Geld|url=http://www.auto-motor-und-sport.de/fahrberichte/bmw-740i-e38-ab-1500-euro-bmw-flaggschif-mit-v8-fuer-kleines-geld-9338635.html|website=Auto, Motor und Sport|accessdate=12 April 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn February 1991, the final production design for the new 7 Series was approved by the board 36 months ahead of scheduled start of production for February 17, 1994.<ref name=\"topspeed\"/> On April 27, 1993 German design patents were filed featuring a pre-production prototype as a design representation.<ref>{{cite web|title=Registerauskunft zum Design  Designnummer: M9303460-0001|url=https://register.dpma.de/DPMAregister/gsm/register?DNR=M9303460-0001|website=Deutsches Patent- und Markenamt|accessdate=12 April 2017}}</ref> Patents were later filed on October 27, 1993 in the United States.<ref>{{cite patent |country=US|number=D0372687|title=Automobile Exterior Body|assign1=Bayerische Motoren Werke Aktiengesellschaft|url=http://pdfpiw.uspto.gov/.piw?PageNum=0&docid=D0372687}}</ref>\n\n== Production ==\nProduction started on July 23, 1993 on pilot production models and US specification variants on January 13, 1994, with series production commencing in April 1994 for June 1994 domestic German launch with the 730i and 740i.<ref name=\"bmw-grouparchiv.de\">https://bmw-grouparchiv.de/research/detail/index.xhtml?id=3843495</ref> US-specification cars entered production in September 1994, for November 1994 launch. On February 18, 1994, the E38 BMW 7 Series was unveiled for the 1995 model year via a BMW press release. The 750i production began in November 1994, in advance of its January 1995 launch.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Pisano|first1=Gary|title=BMW: The 7-Series Project (A)|date=1992|publisher=Harvard Business School.|url=https://archive.org/details/BMWThe7SeriesProject|accessdate=14 November 2016}}</ref><ref>http://www.e38registry.org/e38-production-numbers/</ref>\n\nThe last E38 (a silver 740i with a black leather interior) rolled off BMW's assembly line on July 27, 2001<ref>{{cite book|last1=Lewin|first1=Tony|title=The Complete Book of BMW|date=2004|publisher=Motorbooks|isbn=0760319510|page=209|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=AZKFLcLybIMC&pg=PA209&lpg=PA209&dq=generationswechsel+e38&source=bl&ots=o3PwWSp_Qi&sig=HPlWC_k5jKI9iCVdBUD_WMXnmlg&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjEieuoiqrQAhUEMGMKHQENB5MQ6AEIHTAA#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=15 November 2016}}</ref> to make way for the replacement [[BMW E65|E65 7&nbsp;Series]].\n\n== Equipment ==\nSafety features include [[ASC+T]] traction control, [[headlight washer]]s and auto-leveling low beam [[Headlamp#High-intensity discharge .28HID.29|xenon HID headlamps]]. [[Airbag#Side tubular or curtain airbag|Side tubular airbags]] (called \"Head Protection System\") were fitted as standard equipment.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bmwusa.com/7series/740i/equipment/equipment_b.htm |title=Standard and Optional Equipment |publisher=BMW NA|accessdate=14 November 2016| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20010614020948/http://www.bmwusa.com/7series/740i/equipment/equipment_b.htm| archivedate= 2001-06-14 <!--DASHBot-->|url-status = dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=BMW Head Protection System Sets New Standard in Side-Impact Protection in Latest IIHS Crash Test|url=http://www.theautochannel.com/news/press/date/19971030/press007605.html|website=www.theautochannel.com|accessdate=13 April 2017}}</ref> \"Active Comfort Seats\" were introduced in 1998, to improve comfort and reduce fatigue for the driver and front passenger.<ref>{{cite web|title=Active Comfort Seat feature was an ''option'' in addition of<!--sic--> the regular seats|url=http://www.bimmerboard.com/forums/posts/689684|website=www.bimmerboard.com|accessdate=13 April 2017}}</ref> This system uses two fluid-filled bladders which alternate in height.<ref>{{cite web|title=Active Comfort Seat retrofit to the Contour Seat|url=http://www.bimmerboard.com/forums/posts/567475|website=www.bimmerboard.com|accessdate=13 April 2017}}</ref>\n\nOther equipment includes [[Electronic Damper Control]] (called EDC III),  power moonroof, rain-sensing wipers, dual zone [[climate control]], electric drivers seat adjustment and electric steering wheel adjustment.\n\n[[Insulated glazing|Double glazed windows]] were available (called \"dual pane glass\").<ref name=\"security glass\"/> Break resistant [[Laminated glass|laminated \"security glass\"]] was also available, which is known to delaminate. The delamination occurred with the Protection S357A option only, not with normal S352A dual pane windows.<ref name =\"security glass\">{{cite web|title=Security Glass Question|url=https://www.bimmerforums.com/forum/showthread.php?1668374-Security-Glass-Question|website=www.bimmerforums.com|accessdate=13 April 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=750il with bullet proof glass|url=http://www.bimmerfest.com/forums/showthread.php?t=53179|website=www.bimmerfest.com|accessdate=13 April 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Break resistant glass|url=http://www.bimmerfest.com/forums/showthread.php?p=5645040#post5645040|website=Bimmerfest.com|accessdate=17 May 2018|language=en}}</ref> [[Bulletproof glass|Bullet-resistant glass]] was used for the Protection model, with even thicker glass used for the Security model.<ref name=\"security glass\"/>\n\nThe Sport Package included a sport steering wheel, sports seats, sports suspension, \"shadowline\" exterior trim and unique wood trim for the interior.<ref>{{cite web|title=01 740iL - Sport package question|url=http://www.bimmerfest.com/forums/showthread.php?t=469510|website=www.bimmerfest.com|accessdate=13 April 2017}}</ref> Some sports models also included a shorter [[Differential (mechanical device)|differential]] ratio and higher stall speed for the [[torque converter]].<ref>{{cite web|title=2000 BMW 740i Sport \u2013 Quick Test|url=http://www.motortrend.com/cars/bmw/7-series/2000/2000-bmw-740i-sport/|website=www.motortrend.com|accessdate=21 April 2017}}</ref> This allowed for a 0\u201397&nbsp;km/h (60&nbsp;mph) acceleration time of 5.9 seconds.\n\n== In-car electronics ==\n[[File:1998 BMW 740i Individual - Flickr - The Car Spy (14).jpg|thumb|right|Navigation monitor]]\nThe E38 was the first European car to be available with [[automotive navigation system|satellite navigation]],<ref>{{cite book|title=The New BMW 7 Series|date=April 1994|publisher=BMW AG.|page=52|url=https://archive.org/details/TheNewBMW7Series|accessdate=4 May 2017}}</ref> a system called CARIN jointly developed by BMW and [[Philips]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Lotse an Bord|url=http://www.focus.de/auto/neuheiten/auto-lotse-an-bord_aid_146785.html|website=www.focus.de|language=German|accessdate=4 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe in-car entertainment (radio, audio system, satellite navigation, television and communications systems) are part of an automotive communication system called I-bus.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.e38.org/bussystem.pdf |title=BMW Bus System |format=PDF |date= |accessdate=2010-11-06}}</ref>\n\nA \"multi-function\" steering wheel, with controls for the audio, phone, cruise control and air recirculation,<ref name=\"larimer\">{{cite book|last1=Larimer|first1=Fred|title=BMW Buyer's Guide|publisher=MotorBooks International|isbn=9781610608268|page=194|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=_AUwce3kANoC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref> was standard equipment.<ref>{{cite web|title=7' E38 728i Diagram Selection|url=http://www.realoem.com/bmw/en/partgrp?id=GE21-EUR-04-1995-E38-BMW-728i&mg=32|website=www.realoem.com|accessdate=30 April 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Transmissions ==\nA 5-speed [[ZF 5HP transmission|ZF 5HP]] automatic transmission was available on all models.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.zf-group.com/pdf/AppChartpasscartrans.pdf|format=PDF|title=ZF North America Application Chart (automatic)|website=www.zf-group.com|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20030912234148/http://www.zf-group.com/pdf/AppChartpasscartrans.pdf |archivedate=12 September 2003 |url-status = dead}}</ref>\n\nIn some markets, a 5-speed [[manual transmission]] was available for the 725tds, 728i,<ref>{{cite book|title=The BMW 7 Series|date=May 1999|publisher=BMW AG|page=[https://archive.org/details/TheNewBMW7Series_201611/page/n48 46]|url=https://archive.org/details/TheNewBMW7Series_201611|accessdate=15 November 2016}}</ref> 730i,<ref>{{cite web|title=BMW 730i (E38)|url=https://bmw-grouparchiv.de/research/detail/index.xhtml?id=3843495|website=BMW Group Archive|publisher=BMW AG|accessdate=16 November 2016}}</ref> 735i<ref>{{cite web|title=BMW 735i (E38)|url=https://bmw-grouparchiv.de/research/detail/index.xhtml?id=3844489|website=BMW Group Archive|publisher=BMW AG|accessdate=16 November 2016}}</ref> and a 6-speed for the 740i.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bmw-grouparchiv.de/research/detail/index.xhtml?id=3844844|title=BMW 740i (E38)|last=|first=|date=|website=BMW Group Archive|publisher=BMW AG|accessdate=16 November 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Engines ==\n=== Petrol engines ===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|- style=\"vertical-align:middle;\"\n! Model !! Engine !! Power !! Torque !!Years !! Production<ref name=\"e38registry\">{{cite web|title=E38 Production Figures by Model|url=http://www.e38registry.org/e38-production-numbers/|website=www.e38registry.com|accessdate=15 November 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=2|728i || [[BMW M52|M52B28]] <br/> [[Straight-six engine|I6]] || {{convert|142|kW|hp PS|0|abbr=on}}||{{convert|280|Nm|lbft|0|abbr=on}} || 1995\u201309/1998 || 26171\n|-\n| [[BMW M52|M52TUB28]] <br/> I6||{{convert|142|kW|hp PS|0|abbr=on}}||{{convert|280|Nm|lbft|0|abbr=on}} || 09/1998\u20132001 || 12776\n|-\n| rowspan=2|728iL || [[BMW M52|M52B28]] <br/> I6 ||{{convert|142|kW|hp PS|0|abbr=on}}||{{convert|280|Nm|lbft|0|abbr=on}} || 1995\u201309/1998 || 1915\n|-\n| [[BMW M52|M52TUB28]]<br/> I6 ||{{convert|142|kW|hp PS|0|abbr=on}}||{{convert|280|Nm|lbft|0|abbr=on}} || 09/1998\u20132001 ||4901\n|-\n|730i || [[BMW M60|M60B30]] <br/> [[V8 engine|V8]] ||{{convert|160|kW|hp PS|0|abbr=on}}||{{convert|290|Nm|lbft|0|abbr=on}}||1994\