998\u20132001||1671\n|-\n| rowspan=2|750iL || [[BMW M73|M73B54]] <br/> V12 ||{{convert|240|kW|hp PS|0|abbr=on}}||{{convert|490|Nm|lbft|0|abbr=on}} ||1995\u201309/1998||11038\n|-\n| [[BMW M73|M73TUB54]] <br/> V12 ||{{convert|240|kW|hp PS|0|abbr=on}}||{{convert|490|Nm|lbft|0|abbr=on}} ||09/1998\u20132001||4039\n|-\n|750iL P || [[BMW M73|M73TUB54]] <br/> V12 ||{{convert|240|kW|hp PS|0|abbr=on}}||{{convert|490|Nm|lbft|0|abbr=on}} ||09/1998\u20132001||85\n|-\n| rowspan=2|750iL S || [[BMW M73|M73B54]] <br/> V12 ||{{convert|240|kW|hp PS|0|abbr=on}}||{{convert|490|Nm|lbft|0|abbr=on}} ||1995\u201309/1998||253\n|-\n| [[BMW M73|M73TUB54]] <br/> V12 ||{{convert|240|kW|hp PS|0|abbr=on}}||{{convert|490|Nm|lbft|0|abbr=on}} ||09/1998\u20132001||344\n|-\n| rowspan=2|L7 || [[BMW M73|M73B54]] <br/> V12 ||{{convert|240|kW|hp PS|0|abbr=on}}||{{convert|490|Nm|lbft|0|abbr=on}} ||1996\u201309/1998||462\n|-\n| [[BMW M73|M73TUB54]] <br/> V12 ||{{convert|240|kW|hp PS|0|abbr=on}}||{{convert|490|Nm|lbft|0|abbr=on}} ||09/1998\u20132001||437\n|}\n\n=== Diesel engines ===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|- style=\"vertical-align:middle;\"\n! Model !! Engine !! Power !! Torque !!Years !! Production<ref name=\"e38registry\"/>\n|-\n|725tds || [[BMW M51|M51D25]] <br/> [[Straight-six engine|I6]] [[Turbodiesel|turbo]] ||{{convert|105|kW|hp PS|0|abbr=on}}||{{convert|280|Nm|lbft|0|abbr=on}} || 1995\u20132001 || 9053\n|-\n|730d || [[BMW M57|M57D30]]  <br/> I6 turbo ||{{convert|142|kW|hp PS|0|abbr=on}}||{{convert|410|Nm|lbft|0|abbr=on}} || 09/1998\u20132001 || 12336\n|-\n|740d || [[BMW M67|M67D40]]  <br/> V8 Biturbo ||{{convert|180|kW|hp PS|0|abbr=on}}||{{convert|560|Nm|lbft|0|abbr=on}} || 09/1998\u20132001 || 3450\n|}\n\n== Special models ==\n=== L7 ===\nFrom 1997 to 2001, BMW sold an extended wheelbase [[limousine]] model called the L7.<ref>{{cite web|title=BMW L7 (E38)|url=https://bmw-grouparchiv.de/research/detail/index.xhtml?id=3847617|website=BMW Group Archiv|publisher=BMW AG|accessdate=15 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=BMW L7 Brochure|date=2000|publisher=BMW AG|url=http://i.imgur.com/HeyAK2D.jpg|accessdate=14 November 2016}}</ref> The [[wheelbase]] was extended by {{convert|250|mm|in|1|abbr=on}} over the \"iL\" models, resulting in an overall length of {{convert|5.37|m|in|1|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"autoevolution\">{{cite web|title=BMW L7 (E38)|url=https://www.autoevolution.com/cars/bmw-l7-e38-1997.html|website=www.autoevolution.com|accessdate=14 April 2017}}</ref> Features included electrically adjustable rear seats, rear footrests, fold down rear trays, a fridge, rear television screen, video player and a fax machine.<ref name=\"autoevolution\"/><ref>{{cite web|title=1997 BMW L7|url=http://germancarsforsaleblog.com/1997-bmw-750il-l7/|website=www.germancarsforsaleblog.com|accessdate=14 April 2017}}</ref>\n\nBased on the 750iL with a 12-cylinder engine, the L7 has an electronically limited top speed of {{convert|250|km/h|mph|0|abbr=on}}.<ref>{{cite web|title=1998 BMW L7 E38|url=http://www.automobile-catalog.com/make/bmw/7-series_e38/7-series_e38-2l/1998.html|website=www.automobile-catalog.com|accessdate=14 April 2017}}</ref> The L7 was only available in the Middle East, Southeast Asia and Europe, and 899 examples were built.<ref name=\"e38registry\"/> The 2000-2001 models had an optional \"privacy window\" glass partition to separate the driver from the rear passengers.<ref>{{cite web|title=Category Archives - L7|url=http://www.e38registry.org/category/l7/|website=www.e38registry.org|accessdate=14 April 2017}}</ref>\n\n<gallery widths=\"200px\" heights=\"150px\">\nFile:2001 BMW L7 (E38) sedan (2015-02-13) 01.jpg|L7 front\nFile:2001 BMW L7 (E38) sedan (2015-02-13) 02.jpg|L7 rear\nFile:1997 BMW L7 rear interior.jpg|L7 interior\n</gallery>\n\n=== Protection line ===\nThe armoured \"Protection Line\" vehicles were built from 2000\u20132001 and were based on the 740iL and 750iL models.<ref>{{cite web|title=For Sale: Bullet-Proof 2000 BMW 750iL|url=http://www.thetruthaboutcars.com/2012/01/for-sale-2000-bmw-750il-protection/|website=www.thetruthaboutcars.com|accessdate=21 April 2017}}</ref> Security features include body armor, bullet-resistant glass and run-flat tyres.<ref>{{cite web|title=BMW 740iL Protection|url=http://www.caranddriver.com/reviews/bmw-740il-protection-specialty-file|website=www.caranddriver.com|accessdate=21 April 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=For the curious, 750iL vs. 750iL Protection|url=http://www.bimmerboard.com/forums/posts/548179|website=www.bimmerboard.com|accessdate=21 April 2017}}</ref> An intercom system is provided to communicate with people outside the vehicle while the windows and doors are shut.<ref>{{cite web|title=BMW Protection Line- Supplementary Owner\u2019s Handbook|url=http://www.e38.org/1999Manual-7Series-Protection.pdf|website=www.e38.org|accessdate=21 April 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Security line ===\nA High-Security version with protection up to [[EN 1063|B6/7]]<ref>{{cite web|title=BMW 750iL High Security |url=http://www.bmw-ids.com:80/content_limousine3.html |website=bmw-ids.com |accessdate=22 April 2017 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20010123225300/http://www.bmw-ids.com/content_limousine3.html |archivedate=2001-01-23 }}</ref> was also available in Europe,<ref>{{cite book|title=The BMW 7 Series|date=May 1999|publisher=BMW AG|page=[https://archive.org/details/TheNewBMW7Series_201611/page/n15 13]|url=https://archive.org/details/TheNewBMW7Series_201611|accessdate=15 November 2016}}</ref> known internally as the 750iL S. The additional security measures brought an additional weight of {{convert|950|kg|lb|0|abbr=on}} compared to the normal 750iL<ref>{{cite book|title=The BMW 7 Series|date=May 1999|publisher=BMW AG|page=[https://archive.org/details/TheNewBMW7Series_201611/page/n50 48]|url=https://archive.org/details/TheNewBMW7Series_201611|accessdate=15 November 2016}}</ref><ref name = \"Security Line\"/>\nFeatures include explosive cord around the windshield allowing removal of the windshield facilitating escape through it in case of a rollover crash<ref name = \"Security Line\"/> and Hydraulically actuated windows.<ref name = \"Security Line\"/> \nA gas sensor can detect irritants like [[CS gas]] and respond by turning the blower motor off closing the fresh air flaps and all windows.<ref name = \"Security Line\"/> A fire suppression system is triggered by either a button or the detection of extreme temperatures in the engine bay or the vicinity of the fuel tank.<ref name = \"Security Line\"/><ref>{{cite web|title=E38 750iLS Fire extinguishing system tubing|url=http://www.realoem.com/bmw/enUS/showparts?id=GK01-EUR-11-2000-E38-BMW-750iLS&diagId=72_0328|website=RealOEM.com|accessdate=21 April 2017}}</ref> \nA breathing air system is also available which delivers air from a cylinder in the trunk,<ref name = \"Security Line\"/> \nup to three firearms cases designed to fit a [[Heckler & Koch MP5#MP5K|Heckler & Koch MP5K]] were also optionally available<ref name = \"Security Line\"/> as well as spherical gunports in the doors.<ref name =\"Security Line\">{{cite book|title=Security Line. Supplementary Owner's Manual.|date=February 2001|publisher=BMW AG|url=https://bmw-grouparchiv.de/research/detail/index.xhtml?id=3575867|accessdate=21 April 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Hydrogen 750hL ===\n[[File:BMW 750HL front-left 2016 Shanghai Auto Museum.jpg|thumb|Hydrogen BMW 750hL]]\n\nOn May 11, 2000, BMW presented a fleet of fifteen 750hL's in Berlin.<ref name=\"Pressemeldung 2001-11-08\">{{cite web|url=https://www.press.bmwgroup.com/deutschland/article/detail/T0005925DE/ |title=CleanEnergy WorldTour 2001: Finale in Berlin |date=2001-11-08 |accessdate=7 May 2017}}</ref>\nIts twelve-cylinder [[Hydrogen internal combustion engine vehicle|hydrogen combustion]] engine can be operated on both hydrogen and petrol. In operation on hydrogen, it delivers {{convert|150|kW|hp PS|0|abbr=on}}, accelerating from 0 to 100&nbsp;km/h (62&nbsp;mph) in 9.6 seconds and slowing the car to attain a top speed of {{convert|226|km/h|mph|0|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"spiegel\">{{cite web|title=BMW 750hL: Nah am Wasser gebaut|url=http://www.spiegel.de/auto/fahrberichte/bmw-750hl-nah-am-wasser-gebaut-a-76253.html|website=spiegel.de|accessdate=7 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe production of the hydrogen engine was integrated into the regular engine production at the Dingolfing plant. It differs from the conventional petrol engine essentially only in regards to the intake tract with additional injection valves for hydrogen.<ref>{{cite web|title=BMW Introduces World's First Production-Based Hydrogen Powered Car|url=https://www.press.bmwgroup.com/usa/article/detail/T0021959EN_US/bmw-introduces-world-s-first-production-based-hydrogen-powered-car?language=en_US|website=press.bmwgroup.com|accessdate=7 May 2017}}</ref> The hydrogen is stored cryogenically at a temperature of minus 253 degrees Celsius in a double-walled steel tank behind the rear seat back. The hydrogen tank holds 140 litres and allows an additional range of {{convert|350|km|mi|0|abbr=on}}.<ref name = \"spiegel\"/> In addition, the 750hL has a fuel cell rated at {{convert|5|kW|hp PS|0|abbr=on}} at 42 volts. This is not used as a drive unit, but as an [[auxiliary power unit]] (APU) for power supply to the electrical system.<ref>{{cite book|title=Opening Up a New Era of Mobility. BMW Hydrogen 7.|publisher=BMW AG|page=72|url=https://www.wired.com/images_blogs/autopia/files/bmw_hydrogen_7.pdf|accessdate=7 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[Expo 2000]] in Hanover the vehicles were used as shuttles. From February to November 2001 the vehicles were part of the \"CleanEnergy WorldTour 2001\" in the cities of Dubai, Brussels, Milan, Tokyo, Los Angeles and Berlin. By November 2001 the 750hL had achieved a mileage of over 150,000&nbsp;km.<ref>{{cite book|title=Annual Report 2001|publisher=BMW AG|page=166|url=https://ddd.uab.cat/pub/infanu/169241/iaBMWa2001ieng.pdf|accessdate=7 May 2017}}</ref> On the [[N\u00fcrburgring]] the 750hL recorded a time of 9 minutes and 53 seconds while powered by hydrogen.<ref>{{cite web|title=Emission Impossible|url=https://www.press.bmwgroup.com/usa/article/detail/T0021975EN_US/emission-impossible?language=en_US|website=press.bmwgroup.com|accessdate=7 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Alpina B12 ===\n{{main|Alpina B12#B12 5.7 and 6.0 E-KAT (E38)}}\n[[File:Alpina B12 (E38) (16531947875).jpg|thumb|Alpina B12 6.0|alt=]]\n\nBased on the BMW 750i and 750iL, [[Alpina]] introduced the B12 5.7 in 1995 and the B12 6.0 in 1999. In contrast to the cars they are based on, these models are not electronically limited to a top speed of {{convert|250|km/h|mph|0|abbr=on}}, but can attain top speeds of more than {{convert|280|km/h|mph|0|abbr=on}} and {{convert|291|km/h|mph|0|abbr=on}}, respectively.<ref name=\"Alpina E38\" /> According to Alpina the B12 5.7 was the world's first vehicle with an electrically heated metal catalyst as standard.<ref>{{cite web|title=ALPINA Meilensteine|trans-title=|periodical=|publisher=ALPINA Burkard Bovensiepen GmbH + Co. KG|url=http://www.alpina-automobiles.com/de/alpina/meilensteine/|format=|accessdate=2016-04-02|last=|date=|year=|month=|day=|language=German|pages=|quote=}}</ref> The B12 5.7 has a 5.7 litre V12 and the B12 6.0 has a 6.0 litre V12.\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|- style=\"vertical-align:middle;\"\n! Model !! Engine !! Power<ref name=\"Alpina E38\">{{cite web|title=ALPINA Automobile auf Basis der BMW 7er \u2013 E38 -|trans-title=|periodical=|publisher=ALPINA Burkard Bovensiepen GmbH + Co. KG|url=http://www.alpina-automobiles.com/de/produktwelt/modellhistorie/bmw-7er/bmw-7er-e38/|format=|accessdate=2016-04-02|last=|date=|year=|month=|day=|language=German|pages=|quote=}}</ref> !! Torque !!Years<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.alpina-automobiles.com/de/produktwelt/model-history/bmw-7er/bmw-7er-e38/|title=BMW 7er E38: ALPINA Automobiles|website=www.alpina-automobiles.com|access-date=2017-04-22}}</ref>\n!Production<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.alpina-archive.com/?cat=45|title=Alpina-Archive  {{!}}  The Unofficial BMW Alpina homepage \u2013 since 1998|website=www.alpina-archive.com|access-date=2017-04-22}}</ref>\n|-\n|B12 5.7 || [[V12 engine|V12]] ||{{convert|285|kW|hp PS|0|abbr=on}}||{{convert|560|Nm|lbft|0|abbr=on}} || 12/1995\u201308/1998 \n|202\n|-\n|B12 6.0 || V12 ||{{convert|316|kW|hp PS|0|abbr=on}}||{{convert|600|Nm|lbft|0|abbr=on}} || 07/1999\u201307/2001 \n|94\n|}\n\n== North American model range ==\nThe models for sale in the North America were the 740i, 740iL and 750iL, and production began in the second half of 1994. The base prices in 2001 were US$62,900 for the 740i, US$66,900 for the 740iL and US$92,100 for the 750iL.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eastbaybmw.com:80/7_series.html |title=East Bay BMW 7 Series |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20010616230956/http://www.eastbaybmw.com/7_series.html |archivedate=16 June 2001 |url-status = dead}}</ref>\n\nThe 750iL was BMW's [[flagship car|flagship vehicle]],{{Citation needed|date=November 2018}} with a {{convert|5.4|litre|cuin|0|abbr=on}} V12 engine rated at {{convert|322|bhp|kW PS|0|abbr=on}}. A [[wheelbase#Varying wheelbases within nameplate|long-wheelbase variant]] was available for all petrol models.<ref>{{cite book|title=The New BMW 7 Series|date=April 1994|publisher=BMW AG|page=100|url=https://archive.org/details/TheNewBMW7Series|accessdate=18 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=BMW 735iL (E38)|url=https://bmw-grouparchiv.de/research/detail/index.xhtml?id=3890892|website=BMW Group Archive|publisher=BMW AG|accessdate=18 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title=BMW 740iL (E38)|url=https://bmw-grouparchiv.de/research/detail/index.xhtml?id=3845095||website=BMW Group Archive|publisher=BMW AG|access-date=2016-11-18}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=The New BMW 7 Series|date=April 1994|publisher=BMW AG|page=103|url=https://archive.org/details/TheNewBMW7Series|accessdate=18 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bmw-grouparchiv.de/research/detail/index.xhtml?id=3890777|title=BMW 728iL (E38)|website=BMW Group Archive|publisher=BMW AG|access-date=2016-11-18}}</ref>\n\n== Model year changes ==\n{{multiple image\n| align = left\n| direction = horizontal\n| width = 200\n| image1= BMW 750iL E38 (8656790744).jpg\n| caption1= Pre-facelift model\n| image2= BMW 740iL E38 (5500335572).jpg\n| caption2= Pre-facelift model (rear view) \n| image3= 1998 BMW 740i Individual - Flickr - The Car Spy (16).jpg\n| caption3= Interior (pre-facelift)\n}}\n\n===1995===\n* E38 Production begins in 1994, for the 1995 [[model year]]. Initial models were the 725tds, 730i/730iL, 740i/740iL and 750i/750iL.\n* V8 models use a Nikasil bore coating, which experiences failures in countries with high sulfur petrol (''see [[BMW M60#Nikasil damage from high-sulfur fuels|M60]] article'').<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.koalamotorsport.com/article-m60v8.asp  |title=Koala Motorsport - tech-home |publisher=Web.archive.org |date= |accessdate=2010-11-06 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070617084713/http://www.koalamotorsport.com/article-m60v8.asp |archivedate = 2007-06-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Case Overview, Standards for Low-sulfur Gasoline|url=http://lobby.la.psu.edu/024_low-sulfur_gasoline/frameset_sulfur.html|publisher=Penn State University|accessdate=15 November 2016}}</ref>\n* DSC III ([[Electronic Stability Control|Dynamic Stability Control]]) becomes optional on the 740i/740iL and 750i/750iL.\n* 740i/740iL models use [[differential (mechanical device)|differential]] ratio of 3.15,<ref>{{cite web|title=Final Drive  Ratio E38|url=http://workshop-manuals.com/bmw/7_series_e38/740il_m60-2_sal/3_technical_data/33__rear_axle/10__final_drive/5_td__final_drive__ratio_e38/|website=BMW Workshop Manuals|publisher=BMW AG|accessdate=15 November 2016}}</ref> compared with 2.92 for following years.\n* Standard equipment includes dual-zone [[climate control]], electric front seats with a three-position memory for the driver's seat, front-seat [[Airbag#Side tubular or curtain airbag|side tubular airbags]], a six-disc CD changer, and [[satellite navigation]].<ref name=\"topspeed\"/>\n\n===1996===\n* 728i and 735i models introduced\n* [[BMW M62|M62]] engine replaces [[BMW M60|M60]] for V8 models. The [[engine capacity|capacity]] on 740i and 740iL engines increases from 4.0&nbsp;L to 4.4&nbsp;L.\n* An S-EDC electronic sports suspension, onboard TV and [[satellite navigation system]] offered as options.\n\n===1997===\n* Front passenger [[head airbag]]s introduced. In late 1997, E38 7 Series and [[BMW E39|E39 5 Series]] became the world's first cars available with side impact head airbags.<ref>{{cite book|title=AUTOLIV INC. ANNUAL REPORT 1999|page=14|url=https://www.autoliv.com/Investors/Financial%20Reports/AR1999.pdf|accessdate=8 May 2017}}</ref> These are known as \"Inflatable Tubular Structure\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.zodiacautomotive.com/products/side-impact-rollover-protection/inflatable-tubular-structure-its/ |title=Inflatable Tubular Structure (ITS) |accessdate=2015-01-01 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150109083508/http://www.zodiacautomotive.com/products/side-impact-rollover-protection/inflatable-tubular-structure-its/ |archivedate=2015-01-09 }}</ref> or \"Head Protection System\", and were available as optional equipment.<ref>{{cite press release|url= http://www.theautochannel.com/news/press/date/19971030/press007605.html |author=BMW of North America |title=BMW Head Protection System Sets New Standard in Side-Impact Protection in Latest IIHS Crash Test |publisher=Theautochannel.com |date=30 October 1997 |accessdate=16 March 2014}}</ref> These airbags are designed to offer head protection in side impact collisions and also maintained inflation for up to seven seconds for rollover protection.\n* The 750iL (actually a re-badged 740iL)<ref>{{cite web|title=Six Fascinating Facts about BMW 740i|url=http://www.carparts.com/bmw/740i|website=www.carparts.com|accessdate=6 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=James Bond's 1997 BMW 750iL|url=https://www.bimmerforums.com/forum/showthread.php?2335416-James-Bond-s-1997-BMW-750iL-E38|website=www.bimmerforums.com|accessdate=6 May 2017}}</ref> is extensively featured in the 18th James Bond film ''[[Tomorrow Never Dies]]'' starring ''[[Pierce Brosnan]]'' .\n\n===1998 mid-life facelift===\n{{multiple image\n| align = left\n| direction = horizontal\n| width = 200\n| image1= 2001 BMW 728i Automatic 2.8 Front.jpg\n| image2= 2001 BMW 728i Automatic 2.8 Rear.jpg\n| caption2 = BMW 728i (post-facelift) \n| image3= BMW 750iL - Flickr - The Car Spy (9).jpg\n| caption3= Interior (post-facelift)\n}}\n\nThe E38 [[facelift (automotive)|facelift]] (also known as Life-Cycle Impulse) models were introduced in the 1999 [[model year]] (produced from September 1998). The major changes are:\n* Revised styling for headlights and tail-lights.<ref name=\"meeknet\"/>\n* 740d model introduced, powered by the 3.9L [[BMW M67|M67]] V8 twin-turbocharged diesel engine.<ref>{{cite press release|url= https://www.press.bmwgroup.com/south-africa/photoDetail.html?title=30-years-bmw-diesel-engines-bmw-740d-v8-diesel-engine-1998-07-2013&docNo=P90128474 |author=BMW Group Press Club of South Africa |title=30 years BMW diesel engines, BMW 740d, V8 diesel engine (1998) |publisher=BMW Group Press Club of South Africa |date=17 July 2013 |accessdate=5 October 2015}}</ref>\n* 735i and 740i engines upgraded to the \"technical update\" (TU) version of the [[BMW M62|M62]], featuring variable valve timing on the intake camshaft (single-VANOS).<ref name=\"meeknet\">{{cite web|title=Timm's BMW E38 buying guide|url=http://www.meeknet.co.uk/E38/bmw_e38_buying_guide.htm|website=www.meeknet.co.uk|accessdate=10 May 2017}}</ref>\n* 728i engines upgraded to the \"technical update\" (TU) version of the [[BMW M52|M52]], featuring variable valve timing on both camshafts (double-VANOS)\n* Sport Package (ZSP option code) released, including M Sport suspension, Style 37 \"M Parallel\" alloy wheels, Contour seats and shadowline exterior trim.\n* DSCIII [[electronic stability control]] becomes standard on all 7 Series models.{{citation needed|date=May 2017}}\n* [[Head airbag]]s become standard on all 7 Series models.{{citation needed|date=May 2017}}\n\n===1999===\n* The 750 now includes Electric Catalytic Converter, or \"E-CAT\", assemblies. [[Resistance heating|Heating coils]] inside the catalytic converter assemblies are electrified just after engine start, bringing the catalyst up to operating temperature very quickly to qualify the vehicle for [[Low emission vehicle]] (LEV) designation.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|last = Edgar|first = Julian|title = Goodbye 12 volts... hello 42 volts!|url = http://autospeed.com/cms/title_Goodbye-12-volts-hello-42-volts/A_0319/article.html|publisher = Autospeed|accessdate = 2 January 2012|date = 5 October 1999|quote = The current model BMW 750iL has a maximum electrical load of a staggering 428 amps (5.9&nbsp;kW)! In this car, over half of the maximum power load is from the short-term electrical heating of the catalytic converters, with the heating used so that they come up to operating temp quickly}}</ref> This system required the use of a two-battery system. This electric catalytic converter had been fitted since 1995 by [[Alpina]] to their B12 5,7 E-KAT saloon based on the BMW 750i, as it had been developed jointly by Emitec, Alpina and BMW.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.alpina-automobiles.com/en/alpina-world/milestones/ |title=Milestones |access-date=16 December 2016 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150630081940/http://www.alpina-automobiles.com/en/alpina-world/milestones/ |archivedate=30 June 2015 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n* From March, features such as Xenon headlamps, rain-sensitive windshield wipers, headlight washers, GPS navigation, and upgraded audio became standard for US models.{{citation needed|date=May 2017}}\n\n=== 2000 ===\n* Display for satellite navigation upgraded in September to 6.5 inch 16:9 screen.<ref>{{cite web|title=Wide screen on-board monitor|url=http://www.e38.org/widescreennav.pdf|website=www.e38.org|accessdate=13 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=7' E38 750i On-board monitor, wide screen|url=http://www.realoem.com/bmw/en/showparts?id=GG01-EUR-05-2001-E38-BMW-750i&diagId=65_0692|website=www.realoem.com|accessdate=13 May 2017}}</ref>\n* Navigation upgraded to MKIII in September, therefore maps for satellite navigation switch to [[compact disk|CD]] format.<ref>{{cite web|title=Information on the History of Older BMW Navigation Systems|url=https://store.bimmernav.com/blogs/installation-bmw/information-on-the-history-of-older-bmw-navigation-systems|website=www.bimmernav.com|accessdate=13 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=7' E38 750i CD navigation street map|url=http://www.realoem.com/bmw/en/showparts?id=GG01-EUR-05-2001-E38-BMW-750i&diagId=65_0493|website=www.realoem.com|accessdate=13 May 2017}}</ref>\n* A radar-based [[Autonomous cruise control system|adaptive cruise control]] (called Active Cruise Control) became available as an option.<ref>{{cite book|title=Fahrwerkhandbuch|publisher=Springer-Verlag|isbn=9783658019921|page=639|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tcT-AAAAQBAJ&lpg=PA639&ots=y_ln-3tlj4&dq=Aktive+Geschwindigkeitsregelung+bmw+e38&pg=PA639&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=13 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=E38 option costs|url=http://www.meeknet.co.uk/E38/Option_Costs.pdf|website=www.meeknet.co.uk|accessdate=12 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Year 2000 E38 4.0iL pdc sensors and cruise control|url=http://www.bimmerforums.co.uk/forum/f76/bmw-7-year-2000-e38-4-0il-pdc-sensors-cruise-control-t129450/index2.html|website=www.bimmerforums.co.uk|accessdate=12 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n===2001===\n[[File:98-01 BMW 7-Series.jpg|thumb|right|2001 BMW 7 Series (US)]]\n* Cosmetic changes including body-colored side skirts and bumper facias (previously black), clear turn signal lenses (previously amber).\n* Sport package becomes available on 750iL.\n* Additional standard equipment, including a Motorola [[Motorola StarTAC|StarTAC]] or TimePort mobile phone, with [[BMW Assist]] telemetry system.\n\n==Film==\n[[File:007-BMW.jpg|230px|thumb|right|A BMW 740iL from ''Tomorrow Never Dies'', seen at an exhibition at Museum Industriekultur, Nuremberg.]]\nContributing to the E38's continued popularity was its appearance in several films such as ''[[Tomorrow Never Dies]]'' (750iL), ''[[Bumer]]'' \"\u0411\u0443\u043c\u0435\u0440\" (750iL), ''[[Enemy of the State (film)|Enemy of the State]]'' (740iL), ''[[Invictus (film)|Invictus]]'' (740iL), ''[[Bad Santa]]'' (740iL), ''[[Fun with Dick and Jane (2005 film)|Fun with Dick and Jane]]'' (740iL), ''[[Valley of the Wolves (TV series)]]'' (L7), ''[[Showtime (film)|Showtime]]'' (740i), ''[[The Transporter]]'' (735i) which was a one off manual 750i badged as a 735i,<ref>{{cite web|title=The Car|url=http://www.thetransportermovie.net/the-car|website=thetransportermovie.net|accessdate=23 November 2016}}</ref> ''[[Live Free or Die Hard]]'' (740i), ''[[Transformers]]'' (740iL), ''[[The Game (1997 film)|The Game]]'' (740iL), ''[[The Sum of All Fears (film)|The Sum Of All Fears]]'' and ''[[Les Anges gardiens]]'' (740i). Even though it was the only featured car in the series to be replaced the following year, the E38 (740i) featured in the [[BMW Films#Ambush|BMW Film ''Ambush'']] which was released in fall 2001.\n\nIn the 18th [[James Bond (film series)|James Bond feature film]] ''[[Tomorrow Never Dies]]'', the sixteen E38 cars used during production were modified so they could be driven from the backseat, making it appear that Bond actor [[Pierce Brosnan]] was controlling the car using his mobile phone. The car type is actually a BMW 740iL but they were [[Rebadging|re-badged]] as the 750iL.<ref>https://www.007james.com/articles/list_of_james_bond_cars_part_3.php</ref> One survives today and can be seen at exhibition \u201cTOP SECRET\u201d at Museum Industriekultur, Nuremberg. Besides the 7 Series saloons, BMW also supplied a $14,000 [[BMW R1200C|R1200C motorcycle]]. BMW received the rights to use movie clips from the film in its multimillion-dollar campaign, and during the 1997 holiday season they offered a special promotion that included the R1200C with the purchase of the 750iL.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,290464_2,00.html |title=BOND OF GOLD &#124; Tomorrow Never Dies &#124; Movie News &#124; Movies &#124; Entertainment Weekly &#124; 2 |publisher=Ew.com |date=1997-11-28 |accessdate=2009-07-25}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{commons category|BMW E38}}\n{{reflist}}\n{{BMW cars: 1980s to 2000s}}\n{{BMW cars: 2000s to 2010s}}\n\n[[Category:BMW model codes|E38]]\n[[Category:Cars introduced in 1994]]\n[[Category:2000s cars]]\n[[Category:BMW vehicles|7 Series (E38)]]\n\n[[sv:BMW 7-serie#E38]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox automobile\n| image = BMW 750i E38 (7719664024).jpg\n| name = BMW 7 Series (E38)\n| assembly = Germany: [[Dingolfing]] ([[BMW Group Plant Dingolfing|BMW Plant Dingolfing]])\n| caption = 2001 BMW 750i \n| manufacturer = [[BMW]]\n| production = April 1994\u2013July 27, 2001<br>340,242 units produced<ref name=\"bmw-grouparchiv.de\">https://bmw-grouparchiv.de/research/detail/index.xhtml?id=3843495</ref><ref name=DeAutosab90Kittler>{{cite book |last=Kittler |first=Eberhard |authorlink= |title= Deutsche Autos seit 1990, Band 5|edition=1.|year=2001 |publisher=Motorbuch Verlag |location=Stuttgart |isbn=3-613-02128-5}}</ref><ref>''Auto Katalog'', 2003 edition, p. 312. Note: Figures include early E65 production.</ref>\n| predecessor = [[BMW 7 Series (E32)]]\n| successor = [[BMW 7 Series (E65)]]\n| body_style = 4-door [[sedan (car)|sedan/saloon]]\n| class = [[Full-size]] [[luxury car]] ([[F-segment|F]])\n| related = [[Alpina B12]]\n| engine = {{unbulleted list | '''Petrol:''' | 2.8&nbsp;L [[BMW M52|''M52'']] I6 | 3.0&ndash;4.0&nbsp;L [[BMW M60|''M60'']] V8 | 3.5&ndash;4.4&nbsp;L [[BMW M62|''M62'']] V8 | 5.4&nbsp;L [[BMW M73|''M73'']] V12 | '''Diesel:''' | 2.5&nbsp;L [[BMW M51|''M51'']] [[turbocharged]] I6 | 2.9&nbsp;L [[BMW M57|''M57'']] turbocharged I6| 3.9&nbsp;L [[BMW M67|''M67'']] turbocharged V8 }}\n| layout = [[Front-engine, rear-wheel-drive layout|Front-engine, rear-wheel-drive]]\n| transmission = {{Unbulleted list\n  |5-speed [[manual transmission|manual]]\n  |6-speed manual\n  |5-speed [[automatic transmission|automatic]]\n  }}\n| length = '''SWB:''' {{convert|4984|mm|in|1|abbr=on}} <br>'''LWB:''' {{convert|5124|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}\n| width = {{convert|1862|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}\n| height = '''SWB:''' {{convert|1425|mm|in|1|abbr=on}} <br>'''LWB:''' {{convert|1435|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}\n| weight = {{convert|1710|-|2085|kg|lb||abbr=on}}\n| wheelbase = '''SWB:''' {{convert|2930|mm|in|1|abbr=on}} <br>'''LWB:''' {{convert|3070|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}\n| designer = Boyke Boyer (exterior: 1990&ndash;1991)\n}}\n\nProduced from April 1994 to 2001, the '''BMW E38''' was the third generation of the [[BMW 7 Series]]. The flagship represented an attractive evolution in design language of the prior [[BMW E32|E32]] generation. The new 7 was available with [[straight-six]], [[V8 engine|V8]] and [[V12 engine|V12]] petrol and straight-six and V8 diesel engines. In 2001, the E38 was replaced by the [[BMW E65|E65 7 Series]].\n\nThe E38 was the first car available with [[Airbag#Side tubular or curtain airbag|curtain airbags]]. It was also the first European car to offer [[automotive navigation system|satellite navigation]]<ref>{{cite web|title=20 JAHRE NAVIGATION Was ist aus ihnen geworden?|url=http://www.auto-motor-und-sport.de/testbericht/20-jahre-navigation-was-ist-aus-ihnen-geworden-8398683.html|website=auto-motor-und-sport.de/|accessdate=4 May 2017}}</ref> and the first BMW to offer an in-built television. The E38 was the first 7 Series to be available with a [[diesel engine]].\n\n== Development ==\nIn early 1988, development began on the third generation of the 7 Series.<ref name=\"topspeed\">{{cite web|title=BMW 7 Series - A Look Back|url=http://www.topspeed.com/cars/car-news/bmw-7-seriesa-look-back-ar168860.html|website=www.topspeed.com|accessdate=7 April 2017}}</ref> From 1988 to 1990 styling work was done initially under design director [[Claus Luthe]]<ref>{{cite web|title=BMW car designers|url=http://www.bmwism.com/bmws_designers.htm|website=www.bmwism.com|accessdate=7 April 2017|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6CN8mVEjO?url=http://www.bmwism.com/bmws_designers.htm|archive-date=2012-11-22|url-status = dead}}</ref> (through April 1990, taken over by Dr. [[Wolfgang Reitzle]]), when Boyke Boyer's concept design was chosen and further refined into production form.<ref>{{cite web|title=BMW-Flaggschiff mit V8 f\u00fcr kleines Geld|url=http://www.auto-motor-und-sport.de/fahrberichte/bmw-740i-e38-ab-1500-euro-bmw-flaggschif-mit-v8-fuer-kleines-geld-9338635.html|website=Auto, Motor und Sport|accessdate=12 April 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn February 1991, the final production design for the new 7 Series was approved by the board 36 months ahead of scheduled start of production for February 17, 1994.<ref name=\"topspeed\"/> On April 27, 1993 German design patents were filed featuring a pre-production prototype as a design representation.<ref>{{cite web|title=Registerauskunft zum Design  Designnummer: M9303460-0001|url=https://register.dpma.de/DPMAregister/gsm/register?DNR=M9303460-0001|website=Deutsches Patent- und Markenamt|accessdate=12 April 2017}}</ref> Patents were later filed on October 27, 1993 in the United States.<ref>{{cite patent |country=US|number=D0372687|title=Automobile Exterior Body|assign1=Bayerische Motoren Werke Aktiengesellschaft|url=http://pdfpiw.uspto.gov/.piw?PageNum=0&docid=D0372687}}</ref>\n\n== Production ==\nProduction started on July 23, 1993 on pilot production models and US specification variants on January 13, 1994, with series production commencing in April 1994 for June 1994 domestic German launch with the 730i and 740i.<ref name=\"bmw-grouparchiv.de\">https://bmw-grouparchiv.de/research/detail/index.xhtml?id=3843495</ref> US-specification cars entered production in September 1994, for November 1994 launch. On February 18, 1994, the E38 BMW 7 Series was unveiled for the 1995 model year via a BMW press release. The 750i production began in November 1994, in advance of its January 1995 launch.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Pisano|first1=Gary|title=BMW: The 7-Series Project (A)|date=1992|publisher=Harvard Business School.|url=https://archive.org/details/BMWThe7SeriesProject|accessdate=14 November 2016}}</ref><ref>http://www.e38registry.org/e38-production-numbers/</ref>\n\nThe last E38 (a silver 740i with a black leather interior) rolled off BMW's assembly line on July 27, 2001<ref>{{cite book|last1=Lewin|first1=Tony|title=The Complete Book of BMW|date=2004|publisher=Motorbooks|isbn=0760319510|page=209|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=AZKFLcLybIMC&pg=PA209&lpg=PA209&dq=generationswechsel+e38&source=bl&ots=o3PwWSp_Qi&sig=HPlWC_k5jKI9iCVdBUD_WMXnmlg&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjEieuoiqrQAhUEMGMKHQENB5MQ6AEIHTAA#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=15 November 2016}}</ref> to make way for the replacement [[BMW E65|E65 7&nbsp;Series]].\n\n== Equipment ==\nSafety features include [[ASC+T]] traction control, [[headlight washer]]s and auto-leveling low beam [[Headlamp#High-intensity discharge .28HID.29|xenon HID headlamps]]. [[Airbag#Side tubular or curtain airbag|Side tubular airbags]] (called \"Head Protection System\") were fitted as standard equipment.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bmwusa.com/7series/740i/equipment/equipment_b.htm |title=Standard and Optional Equipment |publisher=BMW NA|accessdate=14 November 2016| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20010614020948/http://www.bmwusa.com/7series/740i/equipment/equipment_b.htm| archivedate= 2001-06-14 <!--DASHBot-->|url-status = dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=BMW Head Protection System Sets New Standard in Side-Impact Protection in Latest IIHS Crash Test|url=http://www.theautochannel.com/news/press/date/19971030/press007605.html|website=www.theautochannel.com|accessdate=13 April 2017}}</ref> \"Active Comfort Seats\" were introduced in 1998, to improve comfort and reduce fatigue for the driver and front passenger.<ref>{{cite web|title=Active Comfort Seat feature was an ''option'' in addition of<!--sic--> the regular seats|url=http://www.bimmerboard.com/forums/posts/689684|website=www.bimmerboard.com|accessdate=13 April 2017}}</ref> This system uses two fluid-filled bladders which alternate in height.<ref>{{cite web|title=Active Comfort Seat retrofit to the Contour Seat|url=http://www.bimmerboard.com/forums/posts/567475|website=www.bimmerboard.com|accessdate=13 April 2017}}</ref>\n\nOther equipment includes [[Electronic Damper Control]] (called EDC III),  power moonroof, rain-sensing wipers, dual zone [[climate control]], electric drivers seat adjustment and electric steering wheel adjustment.\n\n[[Insulated glazing|Double glazed windows]] were available (called \"dual pane glass\").<ref name=\"security glass\"/> Break resistant [[Laminated glass|laminated \"security glass\"]] was also available, which is known to delaminate. The delamination occurred with the Protection S357A option only, not with normal S352A dual pane windows.<ref name =\"security glass\">{{cite web|title=Security Glass Question|url=https://www.bimmerforums.com/forum/showthread.php?1668374-Security-Glass-Question|website=www.bimmerforums.com|accessdate=13 April 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=750il with bullet proof glass|url=http://www.bimmerfest.com/forums/showthread.php?t=53179|website=www.bimmerfest.com|accessdate=13 April 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Break resistant glass|url=http://www.bimmerfest.com/forums/showthread.php?p=5645040#post5645040|website=Bimmerfest.com|accessdate=17 May 2018|language=en}}</ref> [[Bulletproof glass|Bullet-resistant glass]] was used for the Protection model, with even thicker glass used for the Security model.<ref name=\"security glass\"/>\n\nThe Sport Package included a sport steering wheel, sports seats, sports suspension, \"shadowline\" exterior trim and unique wood trim for the interior.<ref>{{cite web|title=01 740iL - Sport package question|url=http://www.bimmerfest.com/forums/showthread.php?t=469510|website=www.bimmerfest.com|accessdate=13 April 2017}}</ref> Some sports models also included a shorter [[Differential (mechanical device)|differential]] ratio and higher stall speed for the [[torque converter]].<ref>{{cite web|title=2000 BMW 740i Sport \u2013 Quick Test|url=http://www.motortrend.com/cars/bmw/7-series/2000/2000-bmw-740i-sport/|website=www.motortrend.com|accessdate=21 April 2017}}</ref> This allowed for a 0\u201397&nbsp;km/h (60&nbsp;mph) acceleration time of 5.9 seconds.\n\n== In-car electronics ==\n[[File:1998 BMW 740i Individual - Flickr - The Car Spy (14).jpg|thumb|right|Navigation monitor]]\nThe E38 was the first European car to be available with [[automotive navigation system|satellite navigation]],<ref>{{cite book|title=The New BMW 7 Series|date=April 1994|publisher=BMW AG.|page=52|url=https://archive.org/details/TheNewBMW7Series|accessdate=4 May 2017}}</ref> a system called CARIN jointly developed by BMW and [[Philips]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Lotse an Bord|url=http://www.focus.de/auto/neuheiten/auto-lotse-an-bord_aid_146785.html|website=www.focus.de|language=German|accessdate=4 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe in-car entertainment (radio, audio system, satellite navigation, television and communications systems) are part of an automotive communication system called I-bus.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.e38.org/bussystem.pdf |title=BMW Bus System |format=PDF |date= |accessdate=2010-11-06}}</ref>\n\nA \"multi-function\" steering wheel, with controls for the audio, phone, cruise control and air recirculation,<ref name=\"larimer\">{{cite book|last1=Larimer|first1=Fred|title=BMW Buyer's Guide|publisher=MotorBooks International|isbn=9781610608268|page=194|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=_AUwce3kANoC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref> was standard equipment.<ref>{{cite web|title=7' E38 728i Diagram Selection|url=http://www.realoem.com/bmw/en/partgrp?id=GE21-EUR-04-1995-E38-BMW-728i&mg=32|website=www.realoem.com|accessdate=30 April 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Transmissions ==\nA 5-speed [[ZF 5HP transmission|ZF 5HP]] automatic transmission was available on all models.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.zf-group.com/pdf/AppChartpasscartrans.pdf|format=PDF|title=ZF North America Application Chart (automatic)|website=www.zf-group.com|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20030912234148/http://www.zf-group.com/pdf/AppChartpasscartrans.pdf |archivedate=12 September 2003 |url-status = dead}}</ref>\n\nIn some markets, a 5-speed [[manual transmission]] was available for the 725tds, 728i,<ref>{{cite book|title=The BMW 7 Series|date=May 1999|publisher=BMW AG|page=[https://archive.org/details/TheNewBMW7Series_201611/page/n48 46]|url=https://archive.org/details/TheNewBMW7Series_201611|accessdate=15 November 2016}}</ref> 730i,<ref>{{cite web|title=BMW 730i (E38)|url=https://bmw-grouparchiv.de/research/detail/index.xhtml?id=3843495|website=BMW Group Archive|publisher=BMW AG|accessdate=16 November 2016}}</ref> 735i<ref>{{cite web|title=BMW 735i (E38)|url=https://bmw-grouparchiv.de/research/detail/index.xhtml?id=3844489|website=BMW Group Archive|publisher=BMW AG|accessdate=16 November 2016}}</ref> and a 6-speed for the 740i.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bmw-grouparchiv.de/research/detail/index.xhtml?id=3844844|title=BMW 740i (E38)|last=|first=|date=|website=BMW Group Archive|publisher=BMW AG|accessdate=16 November 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Engines ==\n=== Petrol engines ===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|- style=\"vertical-align:middle;\"