d Milan and Chievo in Bologna, but with fans welcome.\n\nMilan outnumbered every other team for the highest number of season ticket holders with 37,000, with Inter not far behind with 35,000 season ticket holders.\n\nThe lowest attendance for the season was recorded in the Ascoli vs Cagliari match, in the final day of the league, that attracted a mere 2,800 people.\n\n== Number of teams by region ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!\n![[Regions of Italy|Region]]\n!Number of teams\n!Teams\n|-\n|1\n|{{flag|Tuscany}}||align=center|4||align=center|[[Empoli F.C.|Empoli]], [[ACF Fiorentina|Fiorentina]], [[AS Livorno Calcio|Livorno]] and [[A.C. Siena|Siena]]\n|-\n|rowspan=2|2\n|{{flag|Lombardy}}||align=center|3||align=center|[[Atalanta BC|Atalanta]], [[Inter Milan|Internazionale]] and [[A.C. Milan|Milan]]\n|-\n|{{flag|Sicily}}||align=center|3||align=center|[[Calcio Catania|Catania]], [[F.C. Messina Peloro|Messina]] and [[U.S. Citt\u00e0 di Palermo|Palermo]]\n|-\n|4\n|{{flag|Lazio}}||align=center|2||align=center|[[S.S. Lazio|Lazio]] and [[A.S. Roma|Roma]]\n|-\n|rowspan=8|5\n|{{flag|Calabria}}||align=center|1||align=center|[[Reggina Calcio|Reggina]]\n|-\n|{{flag|Emilia-Romagna}}||align=center|1||align=center|[[Parma F.C.|Parma]]\n|-\n|{{flag|Friuli-Venezia Giulia}}||align=center|1||align=center|[[Udinese Calcio|Udinese]]\n|-\n|{{flag|Liguria}}||align=center|1||align=center|[[U.C. Sampdoria|Sampdoria]]\n|-\n|{{flag|Marche}}||align=center|1||align=center|[[Ascoli Calcio 1898|Ascoli]]\n|-\n|{{flag|Piedmont}}||align=center|1||align=center|[[Torino F.C.|Torino]]\n|-\n|{{flag|Sardinia}}||align=center|1||align=center|[[Cagliari Calcio|Cagliari]]\n|-\n|{{flag|Veneto}}||align=center|1||align=center|[[A.C. Chievo Verona|Chievo]]\n|-\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[2006\u201307 Serie B]]\n* [[2006\u201307 Coppa Italia]]\n* [[List of Italian football transfers winter 2006\u201307|List of Italian football transfers 2006-07]]\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.rsssf.com/tablesi/ital07.html] - All results on [[Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation|RSSSF]] Website.\n* [http://www.footballsquads.co.uk/italy/2006-2007/seriea.htm 2006/2007 Serie A Squads] - (www.footballsquads.com)\n\n{{Serie A seasons}}\n{{2006\u201307 in Italian football}}\n{{2006\u201307 in European football (UEFA)}}\n\n{{Portal bar|Association football|Italy}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:2006-07 Serie A}}\n[[Category:Serie A seasons]]\n[[Category:2006\u201307 in European association football leagues|Italy]]\n[[Category:2006\u201307 in Italian football leagues|1]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox football league season\n| competition        = [[Serie A]]\n| season             = [[2006\u201307 in Italian football|2006\u201307]]\n| winners            = [[Inter Milan|Internazionale]]<br /> 15th title\n| relegated          = [[A.C. ChievoVerona|Chievo]]<br/>[[Ascoli Picchio F.C. 1898|Ascoli]]<br/>[[A.C.R. Messina|Messina]]\n| continentalcup1    = [[2007\u201308 UEFA Champions League|Champions League]]\n| continentalcup1 qualifiers = [[Inter Milan|Internazionale]]<br/>[[A.S. Roma|Roma]]<br/>[[S.S. Lazio|Lazio]]<br/>[[A.C. Milan|Milan]]\n| continentalcup2    = [[2007\u201308 UEFA Cup|UEFA Cup]]\n| continentalcup2 qualifiers = [[U.S. Citt\u00e0 di Palermo|Palermo]]<br/>[[ACF Fiorentina|Fiorentina]]<br/>[[Empoli F.C.|Empoli]]\n| continentalcup3    = [[2007 UEFA Intertoto Cup|Intertoto Cup]]\n| continentalcup3 qualifiers = [[Sampdoria]]\n| league topscorer   = [[Francesco Totti]] <br><small>(26 goals)</small>\n| highest scoring    = [[A.S. Roma|Roma]] 7\u20130 [[Calcio Catania|Catania]]\n| matches            = 380\n| total goals        = 969\n| average attendance = 19,720\n| prevseason         = [[2005\u201306 Serie A|2005\u201306]]\n| nextseason         = [[2007\u201308 Serie A|2007\u201308]]\n| extra information  = \n}}\n\nThe '''2006\u201307 Serie A''' (known as the [[Serie A]] [[Telecom Italia Mobile|TIM]] for sponsorship reasons) was the 105th season of top-tier Italian [[association football|football]], the 75th in a [[round-robin tournament]]. It was scheduled to begin on 26 and 27 August, but was postponed to 2 September 2006 due to the [[2006 Italian football scandal]], which led to the absence of [[Juventus F.C.|Juventus]]. On 22 April 2007, [[Inter Milan|Internazionale]] became Serie A champions after defeating [[S.S. Robur Siena|Siena]], as [[A.S. Roma|Roma]]'s loss to [[Atalanta B.C.|Atalanta]] left Inter with a 16-point advantage with five matches to play.\n[[File:Serie A 2006-07 2.png|thumb|325px|right|2006\u201307 Serie A teams distribution]]\n\n==Events==\n\n===2006 Italian football scandal===\n{{main|2006 Italian football scandal}}\nFollowing the Serie A scandal of 2006, [[Juventus F.C.|Juventus]] was relegated to [[Serie B]] and deducted 9 points. [[ACF Fiorentina|Fiorentina]], [[A.C. Milan|Milan]] and [[S.S. Lazio|Lazio]], were deducted 15, 8 and 3 points respectively but were not relegated. Consequently, [[U.S. Lecce|Lecce]], [[A.C.R. Messina|Messina]] and [[Treviso F.B.C. 1993|Treviso]], originally slated for relegation to Serie B, were retained in Serie A, but after [[ACF Fiorentina|Fiorentina]] and [[S.S. Lazio|Lazio]] we're not relegated result in relegation of [[U.S. Lecce|Lecce]] and [[Treviso F.B.C. 1993|Treviso]], thereby keeping the top table at 20 teams.\n\nAs part of another inquiry, [[Urbs Sportiva Reggina 1914|Reggina]] were handed a 15-point penalty but were allowed to remain in Serie A.<ref name=\"reggina3\">[http://www.theworldgame.com.au/home/index.php?pid=st&cid=74227 \"Reggina to stay in Serie A\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060820101836/http://www.theworldgame.com.au/home/index.php?pid=st&cid=74227 |date=2006-08-20 }}, ''The World Game'', 18 August 2006.</ref> This penalty was reduced to 11 points on appeal.\n\n===League halting of February 2007===\n{{main|2007 Catania football violence}}\n\nOn 2 February 2007, police officer [[Filippo Raciti]] was killed outside the [[Stadio Angelo Massimino]], [[Catania]], in football-related violence during the [[Sicilian derby]] between rivals [[Calcio Catania|Catania]] and [[U.S. Citt\u00e0 di Palermo|Palermo]].<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/6326513.stm \"Italian league halted by violence\"].</ref> The match, originally scheduled for 4 February at 3pm, was exceptionally advanced on Friday at 6pm under request of Catania because of the simultaneity with the [[St. Agatha]] local celebrations.\n\nThe dramatic Sicilian derby events, which followed the murder of Ermanno Licursi, an amateur club manager, beaten to death during a riot in a [[Terza Categoria]] league match, led Commissioner [[Luca Pancalli]] to call a stop to all football matches in Italy, including Serie A fixtures. Pancalli noted how the league fixtures would not start again until a solution to the violence issue in Italian football is found. The week after, a special law by the government enforced the measures to be taken against violence in football stadia and forbade the presence of supporters inside stadia which didn't agree with mandatory security dispositions, thus enabling Italian football to go on with half of the matches played without audience.\n\nFollowing the events, Catania was prohibited to play its home matches at Stadio Angelo Massimino for the remaining part of the season, and the club was also forced to play its home matches in neutral grounds without spectators (''a porte chiuse'', behind closed doors). Several other Italian stadia were closed too because of security reasons, and reopened only once they would have passed several safety requirements. All stadiums were successfully reopened for April, with Stadio Massimino's exception. Catania's home matches were successively allowed to be attended by spectators, yet on neutral ground, as from 13 May.\n\n===Dominant Inter===\nWith their victory over [[S.S. Robur Siena|Siena]] on 22 April 2007, [[Inter Milan|Internazionale]] captured the 2006\u201307 Serie A title (the 15th ''[[Scudetto]]'' in their club history) by moving 16 points clear of second-place [[A.S. Roma|Roma]] with five matches to play. Inter's dominant effort marked the defence of the title they were awarded in the wake of the ''Calciopoli'' scandal, and their first ''Scudetto'' claimed on the field since 28 May 1989.<ref name=\"inter1\">[http://www.channel4.com/sport/football_italia/sa0607/int-rom.html \"Inter-Roma match recap\"], ''Channel 4'', 18 April 2007.</ref> Clinching with five matches remaining, Inter tied the Serie A record for earliest title claim (along with [[Torino F.C.|Torino]] in the [[1947\u201348 Serie A]]). The team also broke the record for most consecutive wins with a 17 match winning streak.\n\n===Relegation battle===\nWith Messina and Ascoli already relegated, there was only one relegation slot left to be decided in the last matchday, with [[Parma F.C.|Parma]] (39 points), [[A.C. ChievoVerona|Chievo]] (39), [[Calcio Catania|Catania]] (38), Siena (37) and Reggina (37) involved in the battle. The key match in the relegation battle was widely expected to be Catania\u2013Chievo, to be played in [[Bologna]] because of the forced closure of Stadio Angelo Massimino by the [[Italian Football Federation]] (FIGC) following the February 2007 infamous riots in the Sicilian derby. The match ended in a 2\u20130 win for Catania; due to the contemporary wins of Parma, Siena and Reggina, Chievo were therefore relegated to Serie B.\n\n==Team details==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n! Club\n! City\n! Stadium\n! 2005\u201306 season\n! Team season\n|-\n| [[Ascoli Picchio F.C. 1898|Ascoli]]\n| [[Ascoli Piceno]]\n| [[Stadio Cino e Lillo Del Duca]]\n| [[2005\u201306 Serie A|10th in Serie A]]\n| [[2006\u201307 Ascoli Calcio 1898 season|Season]]\n|-\n| [[Atalanta B.C.|Atalanta]]\n| [[Bergamo]]\n| [[Stadio Atleti Azzurri d'Italia]] \n| [[2005\u201306 Serie B|Serie B Champions]] \n| [[2006\u201307 Atalanta B.C. season|Season]]\n|-\n| [[Cagliari Calcio|Cagliari]]\n| [[Cagliari]]\n| [[Stadio Sant'Elia]]\n| [[2005\u201306 Serie A|14th in Serie A]]\n| [[2006\u201307 Cagliari Calcio season|Season]]\n|-\n| [[Calcio Catania|Catania]]\n| [[Catania]]\n| [[Stadio Angelo Massimino]]\n| [[2005\u201306 Serie B|Serie B Runners-up]]\n| [[2006\u201307 Calcio Catania season|Season]]\n|-\n| [[A.C. ChievoVerona|Chievo]]\n| [[Verona]]\n| [[Stadio Marcantonio Bentegodi]]\n| [[2005\u201306 Serie A|4th in Serie A]]\n| [[2006\u201307 A.C. ChievoVerona season|Season]]\n|-\n| [[Empoli F.C.|Empoli]]\n| [[Empoli]]\n| [[Stadio Carlo Castellani]]\n| [[2005\u201306 Serie A|7th in Serie A]]\n| [[2006\u201307 Empoli F.C. season|Season]]\n|-\n| [[ACF Fiorentina|Fiorentina]]\n| [[Florence]]\n| [[Stadio Artemio Franchi]]\n| [[2005\u201306 Serie A|9th in Serie A]]\n| [[2006\u201307 ACF Fiorentina season|Season]]\n|-\n| [[Inter Milan|Internazionale]]\n| [[Milan]]\n| [[San Siro]]\n| [[2005\u201306 Serie A|Serie A Champions]]\n| [[2006\u201307 Inter Milan season|Season]]\n|-\n| [[S.S. Lazio|Lazio]]\n| Rome\n| [[Stadio Olimpico]]\n| [[2005\u201306 Serie A|16th in Serie A]]\n| [[2006\u201307 S.S. Lazio season|Season]]\n|-\n| [[A.S. Livorno Calcio|Livorno]]\n| [[Livorno]]\n| [[Stadio Armando Picchi]]\n| [[2005\u201306 Serie A|6th in Serie A]]\n| [[2006\u201307 A.S. Livorno Calcio season|Season]]\n|-\n| [[A.C.R. Messina|Messina]]\n| [[Messina]]\n| [[Stadio San Filippo]]\n| [[2005\u201306 Serie A|17th in Serie A]]\n| [[2006\u201307 F.C. Messina Peloro season|Season]]\n|-\n|[[A.C. Milan|Milan]]\n| [[Milan]]\n| [[San Siro]]\n| [[2005\u201306 Serie A|3rd in Serie A]]\n| [[2006\u201307 A.C. Milan season|Season]]\n|-\n| [[U.S. Citt\u00e0 di Palermo|Palermo]]\n| [[Palermo]]\n| [[Stadio Renzo Barbera]]\n| [[2005\u201306 Serie A|5th in Serie A]]\n| [[2006\u201307 U.S. Citt\u00e0 di Palermo season|Season]]\n|-\n| [[Parma Calcio 1913|Parma]]\n| [[Parma]]\n| [[Stadio Ennio Tardini]]\n| [[2005\u201306 Serie A|8th in Serie A]]\n| [[2006\u201307 Parma F.C. season|S